{"title_page": "Gunnar Berg (politician)", "text_new": "'''Gunnar Berg''' (13 September 1923 \u2013 23 December 2007) was a Norwegian politician for the [[Liberal Party of Norway|Liberal Party]].\n\nHe served as a deputy representative to the [[Storting|Norwegian Parliament]] from [[Nordland]] during the term 1965&ndash;1969.\n\n==References==\n*{{stortingetbio|GUBE}}\n\n<br>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berg, Gunnar}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Norway) politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputy members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Nordland politicians]]\n\n\n{{Norway-politician-1920s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Gunnar Berg''' ( 13 September 1923 \u2013 23 December 2007 ) was a Norwegian politician for the [[Liberal Party of Norway|Liberal Party]].\n\nHe served as a deputy representative to the [[Storting|Norwegian Parliament]] from [[Nordland]] during the term 1965&ndash;1969.\n\n==References==\n*{{stortingetbio|GUBE}}\n\n<br>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berg, Gunnar}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Norway) politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputy members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Nordland politicians]]\n\n\n{{Norway-politician-1920s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jkaharper", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunnar_Berg_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Za\u00efko Langa Langa", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Zaiko Langa Langa\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = Za\u00efko Langa Langa\n| origin           = [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]]\n| genre            = [[Soukous]]\n| years_active     = {{start date|1969}}\u2013present\n| label            = Prozal <small>(since 1983)</small>\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.zaikolangalanga.com}}\n| past_members     = \n}}\n'''Zaiko Langa Langa''' (also spelled '''Za\u00efko Langa Langa''' and in other variants)<ref>The name is not reported and spelled consistently. Some album covers (including those of ''[[Les merveilles du pass\u00e9]]'' and ''[[Zekete Zekete]]'') report the first word as Zaiko, while others use a [[Diaeresis (diacritic)|diaeresis]] (i.e., \"Za\u00efko\"). The official [[web site]] of the band has both variants. \"Langa Langa\" is sometimes written \"Langa-Langa\" (for example on the cover of ''[[Le beau temps]]'', ''[[Zaire-Ghana]]'', ''[[Pacha Labaran]]'' and the ''[[Le meilleurs souvenirs vol. 1|Le meilleurs souvenirs]]'' series). As was common with soukous recordings, many album covers report modified versions of the band name with leading [[epithet]]s such as \"Tout-Choc\" or \"Anti-Choc\" (or both: \"Tout-Choc Anti-Choc Zaiko Langa Langa\").</ref> is a popular [[Contemporary]] band from [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]]. Their music and creativity has greatly influenced Congolese and African popular culture like no other band has done. Voted and crowned band of the century in DR Congo \" Zaiko remain the most influential band ever in the history of African music. The word \"Zaiko\" is a [[portmanteau]] for the [[lingala language|lingala]] phrase ''Zaire ya bankoko'', meaning \"Zaire of our ancestors\", where \"Zaire\" must be read as a reference to the river by that name, now called [[Congo River|Congo]]. The meaning of the phrase \"Langa Langa\" is controversial; according to the band's [[website]], it means \"marvelous\" or \"almighty\".<ref>Stewart, in ''Rumba on the River'' (p. 158), claims that \"Langa Langa\" means \"to get drunk\" in lingala (see [https://books.google.com/books?id=gKEHO1z413EC&pg=PA158&lpg=PA159&dq=%22Zaiko+Langa+Langa%22&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html]). Broughton, ''op cit'', says Langa Langa is the name of an ethnic group.</ref>\n\nFounded in the early 1969 by [[D.V. Moanda]], [[Marcelin Delo]], [[Henry Mongombe]], Olemi Eshar-Eshar dem'belina and [[Andre Bita]], Zaiko Langa Langa survived into the 2000s (decade), and have been largely popular through the decades. Because of their \"rebel\" and \"[[hippie]]\" attitude, and their innovative approach to soukous, they became a symbol of the new generations of post-independence [[Zaire]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gyiTOcnb2yYC&pg=PA463&dq=%22Zaiko+Langa+Langa%22&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Broughton, ''World Music'', p.463]</ref> and are sometimes compared to the [[Rolling Stones]] for their appeal on the Congolese youth.<ref name=\"Biography of Zaiko Langa Langa\">[http://mymusic.alice.it/artist/17724/biography Biography of Zaiko Langa Langa]</ref>\n\nThe band has experienced several personnel changes, and a number of prominent soukous musicians have been in their lineup; examples are [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Dindo Yogo]], [[Evoloko Jocker]], [[N'Yoka Longo]] and [[Bimi Ombale]].<ref>Broughton, ''op. cit.'', p. 463</ref> Several soukous band formed as [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]]s of Zaiko Langa Langa; these include [[Isifi Lokole]], [[Yoka Lokole]], [[Viva La Musica]], [[Grand Zaiko Wa Wa]], [[Langa Langa Stars]], [[Zaiko Familia Dei]], [[Basilique Loningisa]], [[Choc Stars]], [[Anti Choc]], and [[Zaiko Nkolo Mboka]]. This large group of related bands is sometimes referred to as \"Clan Langa Langa\" (i.e., \"the Langa Langa family\").\n\nIn 2000, Zaiko Langa Langa were awarded by the [[Congolese Media Association]] as the best Congolese musical group of the 20th century.<ref>See the \"Palma Res\" section of  [http://www.zaikolangalanga.com Zaiko Langa Langa's official site].</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1969-1974 Early years and the invention of Cavacha===\nThe band was formed on December 24, 1969<ref name=\"Eshar\">https://web.archive.org/web/20090101165302/https://www.digitalcongo.net/article/24067</ref> with the provisional name \"Orchestra Zaiko\". The original lineup was composed of [[Papa Wemba]], [[Mavuela Somo]], [[Evoloko Lay Lay]], [[Teddy Sukami]], [[Oncle Bapius]], [[Zamuangana le meneur]] and [[Manuaku Waku]] (also known as P\u00e9p\u00e9 Fely) and [[N'Yoka Longo]].<ref name=\"Longo\">See ''N'Yoka Longo: The Charismatic Leader of Zaiko Langa Langa''</ref> The band also had a pop section, which was playing before the [[soukous]] section, with [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Mbuta Matima]] and [[Mashakado Mbuta]]. Moanda, Mongombe, Marcelin, Waku, Longo and Bita were all from a former band called [[Bel Guide National]].<ref>See ''Origines of Zaiko'', on the band's [https://web.archive.org/web/20090621234632/http://zaikolangalanga.com/EngZaikoOrigine.htm official site]</ref> They were mostly students of Angolans refugees descent coming from upper-class families of [[Kinshasa]].\n\nThe sound of Zaiko Langa Langa was revolutionary with respect to the soukous tradition. They adopted a more up-tempo beat, abandoned wind instruments and emphasized [[snare drum]]s and lead [[electric guitar]]s (and eventually also [[synthesizer]]s). The percussion rhythms were adapted from traditional Congolese music and the [[sebene]] became more prominent.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4azzvK4AudYC&pg=PA70&dq=%22Zaiko+Langa+Langa%22&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Nuttall, ''Beautiful Ugly'', p.70]</ref> Their vocal lines made a large use of the [[call and response]] schemes. Their frenetic stage shows featured a frontline of four singers.\n\nBecause of these innovations, they are sometimes referred to as the founders of the \"third school\" of Congolese soukous.<ref name=\"Longo\"/> The \"first school\" is probably that of soukous bands of the 1940s, such as [[Wendo Kolosoy]] ans [[Adou Elenga]] while the \"second school\" could be that of [[Le Grand Kall\u00e9 et l'African Jazz]] and [[Franco Luambo]]'s [[OK Jazz]]. While their \"rebel\" attitude, which resembled that of the [[hippie]] movement, earned them the sobriquet of \"Zaire's [[Rolling Stones]]\".<ref name=\"Biography of Zaiko Langa Langa\"/>\n\nZaiko quickly became one of the most popular groups of Zaire and had a large fan base among Kinshasa's juveniles. In the 1970s, Zaiko's singers [[Evoloko Jocker|Evoloko \"Lay Lay\" Joker]], [[Papa Wemba]], [[Gina Efonge]], [[Mavuela Somo]], [[Nyoka Longo]] and [[Bimi Ombale]] popularized a rhythm known as ''[[cavacha]]'' which was dominated by faster drum and melodic faster lead guitar also called [[sebene]]. Also spelled \"[[kavasha]], that was a decade-lasting craze in most of [[East Africa]].\nInspired by the [[Woodstock]] movement, Zaiko will introduced the rhythm [[Wondostoke]] in mid seventies, which was an even faster drums and lead guitar and pop dancing inspired by [[James Brown]].\nIn 1974, Zaiko Langa Langa were amongst the Zairean bands to be invited to play in [[Zaire '74]], a huge musical event celebrating the [[The Rumble in the Jungle|Rumble in the Jungle]].<ref name=\"Longo\"/>\n\n===1975-80 Departures and new members===\nIn 1975 because of a conflict of leadership between [[Anto Evoloko]] and [[Pepe Manuaku]] the band lost some of its most important members in [[Papa Wemba]], [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Mavuela Somo]] and [[Evoloko]] who left to form [[Isifi Lokole]] (with the former three moving on to form [[Yoka Lokale]] in 1976).\nThis first version of [[Zaiko Langa Langa]] will deeply mark Zairian music with hits like [[Mosinzo]] first recorded Zaiko song, [[Francine Keller]], [[La tout beige]], [[Chouchouna]], [[Marceline]], [[Liziba]], [[Joliba]], [[Mbeya Mbeya]], [[Onasis]], [[Eluzam]], [[Vie ya Misolo]], [[Bandoki]], [[Mwana Wabi]], [[Mizou]], [[Zena]], [[BP ya munu]], [[Yo nalinga]] and many more\nAfter a brief period of inactivity, Zaiko Langa Langa returned in action with a new line up of singers consisting of [[Nyoka Longo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Redo Likinga]] and [[Mbua Mashakado]] and released popular songs such as [[Beli Mashakado]], [[Lisapo]], [[Ma coco]], [[Toli Kulumpe]], [[Toli ya Liyanza]], [[Eboza]], [[Yudasi]] and 1975 song of the year [[Elo (song)|Elo]]. In these years Zaiko maintained a prominent position in the soukous scenes, while competing with its own spin-offs such as [[Isifi Melodia]] of [[Anto Evoloko]], [[Yoka Lokole]] of [[Mavuela Somo]], [[Libanko]] of [[Gina Efonge]] whose return into Zaiko will be short and later on in 1977 [[Viva La Musica]] of [[Papa Wemba]]. \n\nThe outcome of the personnel changes in the band was the establishment of [[Pepe Manuaku]] as the new leader and the band production of the latter 1970s are particularly sophisticated both in terms of [[melody]] and [[orchestration]], and the [[choreography]] of the live performance was also richer than it was in the early years. In 1975 too saw the establishment of the longest serving front singers of Zaiko in [[Nyoka Longo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Lengi Lenga]] and [[Likinga Redo]] who will become for fourteen years the face of Zaiko and impose Zaiko as the ultimate heavy weight of youth music in [[Zaire]]. The success of the band was so huge and unprecedented in Zairian music history  especially in releasing outstanding songs like [[Nalali pongi]], [[Zaiko wa wa]], [[Kin Kiesse]], [[Ma (song)|Ma]], [[IMA (song)|IMA]], [[fololo ya nzembo]], [[omibongisa]], [[Cit\u00e9 d'ambiance]], [[Pacha labaran]], [[Sangela]], [[Nadi]], [[Likamuisi]], [[Diana ya mama]], [[Didina]], [[Vera (Congolese song)|Vera]], [[Esikebene]], [[Souvenir Djeni]], [[Mangobo]], [[Misolina]] and many more that all the personnel that have left the band were queuing to return. In 1977, [[Bozi Boziana]] rejoined the group, followed by [[Mashakado Mbuta]] and [[Evoloko]] in 1979.\n\nIn 1979 with a line up of 10 singers namely [[Nyoka Longo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Redo Likings]], [[Mbuta Mashakado]], [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Anto Evoloko]], [[Yenga Yenga]], [[Sheikedan]] and [[Otis Mbuta]]  [[Zaiko]] will be revisited by the demons of division. The band will be divided in two groups hostile to each other and pursuing different music philosophy. [[Anto Evoloko]] will lead his group of [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Lengi Lenga]] and the newcomer [[Yenga Yenga]]. [[Nyoka Longo]] too will lead his group of [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Likinga]], [[Shekedan]]. The two group will release songs that were artistically different of each other, the [[Anto Evoloko]] group will release [[7 sacrament]], [[Kemoussa]], [[Belinda]], [[esengo na bango]], [[Betula]] and others while [[Nyoka Kongo]] group will release [[Pa oki]], [[Cherie nzembo]], [[Moni Amina]], [[Cherie B Wabi]] and many more including best song of the year 1979 [[Sentiment Away]]. The band leader and guitarist [[Pepe Manuaku]] who was more focus into his innovative sounds and collaboration in the [[Ya Toupa]] group where he was experimenting sounds with the pianist [[Ray Lema]] with songs like [[Ange Bokumba]], Revelation, [[Zaiko Wa wa]] however he will try to unite the two groups with songs like [[Obi (song)|Obi]], [[Kwiti Kwiti]] and [[Femme ne pleure pas]] but will fail as many band members considered him partisan and favouring the [[Anto Evoloko]] group. On the other hand, [[Teddy Sukami]] another veteran of the band will focus his attention more in releasing songs with the recording studio group [[Les Casques Bleus]] than with [[Zaiko]] even scoring 1978 song of the year [[Bongo boug\u00e9]] with Les Casques bleus. The conflict will result in 1980 departure of band leader, co-founder and lead-guitarist [[Pepe Manuaku]], taking with him [[Shekedan]] and [[Yenga Yenga]] to start his own band [[Grand Zaiko Wa Wa]].\n\n===1980-88 Departure of Pepe Manuaku and addition of Atalaku===\nFollowing the departure of [[Pepe Manuaku]], [[Roxy Tshimpaka]] (also called [[Grand Niawu]]) became as lead guitarist and [[Mbuta Matima]] became artistic director. During this period Zaiko Langa Langa released many of their most famous songs including [[Crois moi]], [[Amiti\u00e9]], [[Viya (song)|Viya]], [[Essesse]], [[LA Blonde]], [[Kamanzi]], [[Cherie Massa]], [[Lolita]], [[Kinshasa makambo]] and 1981 song of the year [[Fievre mondo]].\n\nHowever there were further internal quarrels and personnel changes with the departure in 1981 of Evoloko, Bozi Boziana and Djo Mali to form [[Langa Langa Stars]], joined a year later by Roxy Tshimpaka. By 1982 N'yoka Longo had become the effective band leader however there were also some unofficial recordings without his involvement or sanction<ref>https://www.totallyradio.com/shows/african-and-global-beat/episodes/78506</ref>.\n\nIn 1982 Zaiko introduced maracas and [[Atalaku]] ('animateur' in French or a specialist vocal typically over the 'sebene') in the band. The Atalaku firstly performed solo by [[Sonnerie]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2019}} in the critically acclaimed album [[tokangi robinet]] brought in the traditional elements into Zaiko and Congolese pop music. The mixture of maracas, African drum play by [[Djerba]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2019}} and Atalaku (traditional animation) now led by Bebe and Nono will bring huge success to the band as well as revolutionized Congolese popular music.\n\nIn 1984, [[Dindo Yogo]] arrived as a singer in the band and quickly became the group's dominant solo vocalist.\n\nDuring this period Zaiko released successful albums regularly. The band was touring Europe and Africa and was the first Zairian band to visit [[Japan]].\n\n===1988-1998 Split to Nkolo Mboka and Familia Dei===\n\nIn 1988 the band experienced another major split, between the two leaders of the group Nyoka Longo and Bimi Ombale. The band was divided in two with every musician choosing his camp between the two leaders who were part of Zaiko since its creation. With [[Meridjo]], [[Bapius]], [[Matima]], [[Zamuangana]] who were part of Zaiko from its creation staying with Nyoka Longo followed by [[Dindo Yogo]] and the band was called then [[Zaiko Langa Langa Nkolo Mboka]], to differentiate it from the band of Bimi Ombale which was called [[Zaiko Langa Langa Familia Dei]] and had [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Ilo Pablo]], [[JP Buse]] and the rest of the musicians that came in the 1980s. Zaiko Langa Langa Familia Dei dissolved in 1986<ref>http://rumbaontheriver.com/zaiko.html</ref>, after which time N'Yoka Longo's group reacquired the original name \"Zaiko Langa Langa\", which has maintained until today. N'Yoka Longo is{{when|date=March 2019}} still the leader of the group.\n\n===1999-present===\n\nIn 1999 a further split came with the dismissal of two other senior members of the band in drummer Meridjo and bassist Bapius, who went on to form the short-lived Zaiko Langa Langa Universel<ref>http://rumbaontheriver.com/zaiko.html</ref>.\n\nIn 2002, Zaiko performed in the mythic arena [[Zenith of Paris]], France. More than 6.000 fans attended. This was considered by many as the renaissance or rebirth of Zaiko. As early as 1988, Zaiko, being very popular at that time, made plan to perform in Zenith but the great split that occurred in the band stopped it for doing so.\n\nZaiko spent 6 and half years in Europe (2002\u201309). Its headquarters ware in Bruxelles, Belgium. But the band gave more concerts in France and other countries around Europe.\nDuring that time in Europe, Zaiko released three albums: Eureka (2002), Empreintes (2004), Recontres (2006). In the last album, Nyoka Longo invited many former Zaiko musicians like Malage, Beniko Popolipo; and a retired Congolese musician [[Tony Dee Bokito]]. He also recruited from Kinshasa, the son of late Dindo Yogo, [[Lola Muana]].\n\nDuring the time the Band was in Europe, Nyoka Longo, in 2006, charged Lola Muana, who was then in Kinshasa, to form a group that would promote Zaiko music in [[D.R.Congo]]. Lola recruited and formed a subsidiary group of Zaiko called [[Les Ganers de Zaiko]]. [[Bapius Muaka]], a longtime guitarist bass player who left the group during a minor split of 1999, joined the Ganers too.\n\nThe group returned in D.R.Congo in January 2009 with only five musicians: Nyoka Longo, [[Doudou Adoula]], [[Chou Lay Evoloko]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Gege Mangaya]], [[Shango Landu]] and Lola Muana. Other members of the group defected and stayed in Europe where they formed a new band named [[Les Stars de Zaiko]] under the leadership of Adamo Ekula. Couple years later, they renamed their new band [[Zaikas Kolo Mboka]].\n\nSince his recruitment in Zaiko, Lola Muana was regarded by many as the principal heir of Zaiko. But in 2009, he was forced to quit the group because of his proposal to have a valid work contract with the group. His request was denied by the President of Zaiko, N'Yoka Longo Mvula Jossart. The son of Evoloko, Shou Lay, who backed Lola's request left the group too. In November 2011, Lola Muana was reinstated in the group.\n\n==Clan Langa Langa==\nZaiko Langa Langa were both influential in their own right and through their many spin-offs. Most of these maintained a strong link to the original formation, and this is often reflected by the names they adopted. The groups that somehow belong to the Zaiko Langa Langa \"[[Franchising|franchise]]\" are collectively known as the \"Clan Langa Langa\". This includes:\n\n* [[Isifi Lokole]] (1974-1978)- [[Papa Wemba]], [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Evoloko Jocker]], [[Mavuela Somo]]\n* [[Yoka Lokole]] (1978-Pr\u00e9sent) - Papa Wemba, Bozi Boziana, Mavuela Somo\n* [[Grand Za\u00efko Wa Wa]] (1981-Pr\u00e9sent) - [[Manuaku Waku]] who was joined by successful singers like [[Shimita]], [[Djo Poster]] among others\n* [[Viva La Musica]] (1977\u20132016) - Papa Wemba, joined by [[Emeneya Mubiala]], [[Dindo Yogo]]\n* [[Tout Grand Libanko]] (1977-Pr\u00e9sent) - [[Gina Efong\u00e9]]\n* [[Choc Stars]] (1983-2019) -  Bozi Boziana, [[Tshimpaka Roxy]] joined by [[Ben Nyamabo]], [[Carlyto Lassa]], [[Defao]]\n* [[L'Orchestre Anti-Choc]] (1985-Pr\u00e9sent) - Bozi Boziana, joined by [[Deyesse Mukangi]], [[Jolie Detta]], [[Dodoli]], [[Walingonda]], [[Fifi Mofude]], etc.\n* [[Langa Langa Stars]] (1981\u20131984) - Evoloko Jocker, Bozi Boziana, Tshimpaka Roxy and [[Djo Mali]]\n* [[Za\u00efko Langa Langa Nkolo Mboka]] - [[N'Yoka Longo]], [[Meridjo]], [[Dindo Yogo]], [[Oncle Bapius]], [[Gilbert Benamayi]], [[Zamuangana]], [[Nono Monzuluku]] and [[Matima]]. They were joined by [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Adamo]], Baroza, [[Shiro Shiro]],\n* [[Za\u00efko Langa Langa Familia Dei]] (1988-1996) - [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Ilo Pablo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Beniko Popolipo]], [[Petit Poisson]], [[Djimi Yaba]]\n* [[Zaiko Universel]] (1999\u20132001)- [[Meridjo]], [[Bapius Muaka]]\n* [[Langa Langa Stars R\u00e9nov\u00e9]] (1981-Pr\u00e9sent) - Evoloko Jocker\n* [[Basilique Loningisa]] (1990-1995)- Bimi Ombale\n* [[Ngwaka Aye]] (1991-2000) - Dindo Yogo\n* [[Les Quatros de Langa Langa]], Papa Wemba, Evoloko, Bozi Boziana, Gina Efonge\n* [[Les Stars de Zaiko]], Now called [[Zaikas Kolo Mboka]] (2009-2011), Adamo Ekula, Petit Poisson, Tshanda, Papy Cocaine, etc.\n* [[Les g\u00e9ants (band)|Les g\u00e9ants]] - [[Koffi Olomide]], [[King Kester Emeneya]], [[P\u00e9p\u00e9 Kall\u00e9]], [[Sam Mangwana]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Madilu System]], [[Rigo Star]]\n* [[Les Super Stars]] - [[Endho Ndumba]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Defao]], [[Beniko Popolipo]]\n* [[Zaire All Stars]] - [[Papa Wemba]], [[Fafa De Molokai]], [[Mpongo Love]]\n* [[Les Asiatiques]] - [[Madilu System]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Lassa Carlyto]]\n\n==Partial discography==\n\n;Albums\n* 1970 : ''Pauline''\n* 1972 : ''L'amoureux decu''\n* 1973 : ''Mete la v\u00e9rit\u00e9, chouchouna'', ''Mbeya Mbeya'', ''Zena''\n* 1974 : ''Liwa ya somo'', ''Mwana Wabi'', ''Mizou'', ''Eluzam'', ''Belinda ya mbongo/Onassis''\n* 1981 : ''Sarah Djenni''\n* 1983 : ''La Tout Neige'' \n* 1984 : ''Bizita'', ''Patchely''\n* 1985 : ''Zaiko Eyi Nkisi''\n* 1985 : ''Eh Ngoss! Eh Ngoss! Eh Ngoss!''\n* 1986 : ''Bongoville ''\n* 1986 : ''Pusa Kuna... Serrez! Serrez!''\n* 1997 : ''Papa Omar''\n* 1987 : ''Bongama Kamata Position''\n* 1987 : ''Subissez les cons\u00e9quences''\n* 1988 : ''Nippon Banzai au Japon''\n* 1989 : ''Jetez l'Eponge''\n* 1990 : ''Zaiko Langa-Langa F. D.''\n* 1990 : ''Ici ca va \"Fungola Motema''\n* 1992 : ''L'Autentique Zaiko Langa Langa''\n* 1992 : ''Jamais sans nous''\n* 1993 : ''Zaire-Ghana'' (recorded in Accra in 1976, produced by [[Henri Bowane]])\n* 1994 : ''Ambiance a Kin'' (Featuring [[Adamo Ekula]], [[Baroza]], [[Malage de Lugendo]])\n* 1995 : ''Avis de recherche''\n* 1995 : ''Zekete Zekete''\n* 1996 : ''Pacha labaran''\n* 1996 : ''[[Saisie en Douane... 20 Ans D\u00e9j\u00e0]]''\n* 1997 : ''Papa Omar''\n* 1997 : ''Onassis''\n* 1997 : ''Muvaro''\n* 1997 : ''Le beau temps''\n* 1997 : ''Bongo bouger''\n* 1997 : ''Backline Lesson One''\n* 1998 : ''Sans Issue''\n* 1999 : ''Poison''\n* 2000 : ''Etumba ya la vie'' (An album by a dissident group of Meridjo: [[Zaiko Universel]])\n* 2001 : ''Legend''\n* 2001 : ''Feeling''\n* 2002 : ''Anthologie''\n* 2003 : ''Sentiment Awa / Essesse''\n* 2003 : ''Eureka!''\n* 2004 : ''[[Empreinte]]''\n* 2006 : ''Rencontres''\n* 2011 : ''Bande Annonce''\n\n;Contributing artist\n* 1994 : ''[[The Rough Guide to World Music]]''\n\n==References==\n*[http://kenyapage.net/music/zaiko.html Africa Music Centre]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.zaikolangalanga.com Official Zaiko Langa Langa homepage]\n*[http://www.documen.tv/asset/Zaiko_Langa_Langa.html \" Zaiko Langa Langa \"]  1999 Documentary 52'\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Zaiko Langa Langa\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = Za\u00efko Langa Langa\n| origin           = [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]]\n| genre            = [[Soukous]]\n| years_active     = {{start date|1969}}\u2013present\n| label            = Prozal <small>(since 1983)<small>\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.zaikolangalanga.com}}\n| past_members     = \n}}\n'''Zaiko Langa Langa''' (also spelled '''Za\u00efko Langa Langa''' and in other variants)<ref>The name is not reported and spelled consistently. Some album covers (including those of ''[[Les merveilles du pass\u00e9]]'' and ''[[Zekete Zekete]]'') report the first word as Zaiko, while others use a [[Diaeresis (diacritic)|diaeresis]] (i.e., \"Za\u00efko\"). The official [[web site]] of the band has both variants. \"Langa Langa\" is sometimes written \"Langa-Langa\" (for example on the cover of ''[[Le beau temps]]'', ''[[Zaire-Ghana]]'', ''[[Pacha Labaran]]'' and the ''[[Le meilleurs souvenirs vol. 1|Le meilleurs souvenirs]]'' series). As was common with soukous recordings, many album covers report modified versions of the band name with leading [[epithet]]s such as \"Tout-Choc\" or \"Anti-Choc\" (or both: \"Tout-Choc Anti-Choc Zaiko Langa Langa\").</ref> is a popular [[Contemporary]] band from [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]]. Their music and creativity has greatly influenced Congolese and African popular culture like no other band has done. Voted and crowned band of the century in DR Congo \" Zaiko remain the most influential band ever in the history of African music. The word \"Zaiko\" is a [[portmanteau]] for the [[lingala language|lingala]] phrase ''Zaire ya bankoko'', meaning \"Zaire of our ancestors\", where \"Zaire\" must be read as a reference to the river by that name, now called [[Congo River|Congo]]. The meaning of the phrase \"Langa Langa\" is controversial; according to the band's [[website]], it means \"marvelous\" or \"almighty\".<ref>Stewart, in ''Rumba on the River'' (p. 158), claims that \"Langa Langa\" means \"to get drunk\" in lingala (see [https://books.google.com/books?id=gKEHO1z413EC&pg=PA158&lpg=PA159&dq=%22Zaiko+Langa+Langa%22&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html]). Broughton, ''op cit'', says Langa Langa is the name of an ethnic group.</ref>\n\nFounded in the early 1969 by [[D.V. Moanda]], [[Marcelin Delo]], [[Henry Mongombe]], Olemi Eshar-Eshar dem'belina and [[Andre Bita]], Zaiko Langa Langa survived into the 2000s (decade), and have been largely popular through the decades. Because of their \"rebel\" and \"[[hippie]]\" attitude, and their innovative approach to soukous, they became a symbol of the new generations of post-independence [[Zaire]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gyiTOcnb2yYC&pg=PA463&dq=%22Zaiko+Langa+Langa%22&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Broughton, ''World Music'', p.463]</ref> and are sometimes compared to the [[Rolling Stones]] for their appeal on the Congolese youth.<ref name=\"Biography of Zaiko Langa Langa\">[http://mymusic.alice.it/artist/17724/biography Biography of Zaiko Langa Langa]</ref>\n\nThe band has experienced several personnel changes, and a number of prominent soukous musicians have been in their lineup; examples are [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Dindo Yogo]], [[Evoloko Jocker]], [[N'Yoka Longo]] and [[Bimi Ombale]].<ref>Broughton, ''op. cit.'', p. 463</ref> Several soukous band formed as [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]]s of Zaiko Langa Langa; these include [[Isifi Lokole]], [[Yoka Lokole]], [[Viva La Musica]], [[Grand Zaiko Wa Wa]], [[Langa Langa Stars]], [[Zaiko Familia Dei]], [[Basilique Loningisa]], [[Choc Stars]], [[Anti Choc]], and [[Zaiko Nkolo Mboka]]. This large group of related bands is sometimes referred to as \"Clan Langa Langa\" (i.e., \"the Langa Langa family\").\n\nIn 2000, Zaiko Langa Langa were awarded by the [[Congolese Media Association]] as the best Congolese musical group of the 20th century.<ref>See the \"Palma Res\" section of  [http://www.zaikolangalanga.com Zaiko Langa Langa's official site].</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1969-1974 Early years and the invention of Cavacha===\nThe band was formed on December 24, 1969<ref name=\"Eshar\">https://web.archive.org/web/20090101165302/https://www.digitalcongo.net/article/24067</ref> with the provisional name \"Orchestra Zaiko\". The original lineup was composed of [[Papa Wemba]], [[Mavuela Somo]], [[Evoloko Lay Lay]], [[Teddy Sukami]], [[Oncle Bapius]], [[Zamuangana le meneur]] and [[Manuaku Waku]] (also known as P\u00e9p\u00e9 Fely) and [[N'Yoka Longo]].<ref name=\"Longo\">See ''N'Yoka Longo: The Charismatic Leader of Zaiko Langa Langa''</ref> The band also had a pop section, which was playing before the [[soukous]] section, with [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Mbuta Matima]] and [[Mashakado Mbuta]]. Moanda, Mongombe, Marcelin, Waku, Longo and Bita were all from a former band called [[Bel Guide National]].<ref>See ''Origines of Zaiko'', on the band's [https://web.archive.org/web/20090621234632/http://zaikolangalanga.com/EngZaikoOrigine.htm official site]</ref> They were mostly students of Angolans refugees descent coming from upper-class families of [[Kinshasa]].\n\nThe sound of Zaiko Langa Langa was revolutionary with respect to the soukous tradition. They adopted a more up-tempo beat, abandoned wind instruments and emphasized [[snare drum]]s and lead [[electric guitar]]s (and eventually also [[synthesizer]]s). The percussion rhythms were adapted from traditional Congolese music and the [[sebene]] became more prominent.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4azzvK4AudYC&pg=PA70&dq=%22Zaiko+Langa+Langa%22&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Nuttall, ''Beautiful Ugly'', p.70]</ref> Their vocal lines made a large use of the [[call and response]] schemes. Their frenetic stage shows featured a frontline of four singers.\n\nBecause of these innovations, they are sometimes referred to as the founders of the \"third school\" of Congolese soukous.<ref name=\"Longo\"/> The \"first school\" is probably that of soukous bands of the 1940s, such as [[Wendo Kolosoy]] ans [[Adou Elenga]] while the \"second school\" could be that of [[Le Grand Kall\u00e9 et l'African Jazz]] and [[Franco Luambo]]'s [[OK Jazz]]. While their \"rebel\" attitude, which resembled that of the [[hippie]] movement, earned them the sobriquet of \"Zaire's [[Rolling Stones]]\".<ref name=\"Biography of Zaiko Langa Langa\"/>\n\nZaiko quickly became one of the most popular groups of Zaire and had a large fan base among Kinshasa's juveniles. In the 1970s, Zaiko's singers [[Evoloko Jocker|Evoloko \"Lay Lay\" Joker]], [[Papa Wemba]], [[Gina Efonge]], [[Mavuela Somo]], [[Nyoka Longo]] and [[Bimi Ombale]] popularized a rhythm known as ''[[cavacha]]'' which was dominated by faster drum and melodic faster lead guitar also called [[sebene]]. Also spelled \"[[kavasha]], that was a decade-lasting craze in most of [[East Africa]].\nInspired by the [[Woodstock]] movement, Zaiko will introduced the rhythm [[Wondostoke]] in mid seventies, which was an even faster drums and lead guitar and pop dancing inspired by [[James Brown]].\nIn 1974, Zaiko Langa Langa were amongst the Zairean bands to be invited to play in [[Zaire '74]], a huge musical event celebrating the [[The Rumble in the Jungle|Rumble in the Jungle]].<ref name=\"Longo\"/>\n\n===1975-80 Departures and new members===\nIn 1975 because of a conflict of leadership between [[Anto Evoloko]] and [[Pepe Manuaku]] the band lost some of its most important members in [[Papa Wemba]], [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Mavuela Somo]] and [[Evoloko]] who left to form [[Isifi Lokole]] (with the former three moving on to form [[Yoka Lokale]] in 1976).\nThis first version of [[Zaiko Langa Langa]] will deeply mark Zairian music with hits like [[Mosinzo]] first recorded Zaiko song, [[Francine Keller]], [[La tout beige]], [[Chouchouna]], [[Marceline]], [[Liziba]], [[Joliba]], [[Mbeya Mbeya]], [[Onasis]], [[Eluzam]], [[Vie ya Misolo]], [[Bandoki]], [[Mwana Wabi]], [[Mizou]], [[Zena]], [[BP ya munu]], [[Yo nalinga]] and many more\nAfter a brief period of inactivity, Zaiko Langa Langa returned in action with a new line up of singers consisting of [[Nyoka Longo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Redo Likinga]] and [[Mbua Mashakado]] and released popular songs such as [[Beli Mashakado]], [[Lisapo]], [[Ma coco]], [[Toli Kulumpe]], [[Toli ya Liyanza]], [[Eboza]], [[Yudasi]] and 1975 song of the year [[Elo (song)|Elo]]. In these years Zaiko maintained a prominent position in the soukous scenes, while competing with its own spin-offs such as [[Isifi Melodia]] of [[Anto Evoloko]], [[Yoka Lokole]] of [[Mavuela Somo]], [[Libanko]] of [[Gina Efonge]] whose return into Zaiko will be short and later on in 1977 [[Viva La Musica]] of [[Papa Wemba]]. \n\nThe outcome of the personnel changes in the band was the establishment of [[Pepe Manuaku]] as the new leader and the band production of the latter 1970s are particularly sophisticated both in terms of [[melody]] and [[orchestration]], and the [[choreography]] of the live performance was also richer than it was in the early years. In 1975 too saw the establishment of the longest serving front singers of Zaiko in [[Nyoka Longo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Lengi Lenga]] and [[Likinga Redo]] who will become for fourteen years the face of Zaiko and impose Zaiko as the ultimate heavy weight of youth music in [[Zaire]]. The success of the band was so huge and unprecedented in Zairian music history  especially in releasing outstanding songs like [[Nalali pongi]], [[Zaiko wa wa]], [[Kin Kiesse]], [[Ma (song)|Ma]], [[IMA (song)|IMA]], [[fololo ya nzembo]], [[omibongisa]], [[Cit\u00e9 d'ambiance]], [[Pacha labaran]], [[Sangela]], [[Nadi]], [[Likamuisi]], [[Diana ya mama]], [[Didina]], [[Vera (Congolese song)|Vera]], [[Esikebene]], [[Souvenir Djeni]], [[Mangobo]], [[Misolina]] and many more that all the personnel that have left the band were queuing to return. In 1977, [[Bozi Boziana]] rejoined the group, followed by [[Mashakado Mbuta]] and [[Evoloko]] in 1979.\n\nIn 1979 with a line up of 10 singers namely [[Nyoka Longo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Redo Likings]], [[Mbuta Mashakado]], [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Anto Evoloko]], [[Yenga Yenga]], [[Sheikedan]] and [[Otis Mbuta]]  [[Zaiko]] will be revisited by the demons of division. The band will be divided in two groups hostile to each other and pursuing different music philosophy. [[Anto Evoloko]] will lead his group of [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Lengi Lenga]] and the newcomer [[Yenga Yenga]]. [[Nyoka Longo]] too will lead his group of [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Likinga]], [[Shekedan]]. The two group will release songs that were artistically different of each other, the [[Anto Evoloko]] group will release [[7 sacrament]], [[Kemoussa]], [[Belinda]], [[esengo na bango]], [[Betula]] and others while [[Nyoka Kongo]] group will release [[Pa oki]], [[Cherie nzembo]], [[Moni Amina]], [[Cherie B Wabi]] and many more including best song of the year 1979 [[Sentiment Away]]. The band leader and guitarist [[Pepe Manuaku]] who was more focus into his innovative sounds and collaboration in the [[Ya Toupa]] group where he was experimenting sounds with the pianist [[Ray Lema]] with songs like [[Ange Bokumba]], Revelation, [[Zaiko Wa wa]] however he will try to unite the two groups with songs like [[Obi (song)|Obi]], [[Kwiti Kwiti]] and [[Femme ne pleure pas]] but will fail as many band members considered him partisan and favouring the [[Anto Evoloko]] group. On the other hand, [[Teddy Sukami]] another veteran of the band will focus his attention more in releasing songs with the recording studio group [[Les Casques Bleus]] than with [[Zaiko]] even scoring 1978 song of the year [[Bongo boug\u00e9]] with Les Casques bleus. The conflict will result in 1980 departure of band leader, co-founder and lead-guitarist [[Pepe Manuaku]], taking with him [[Shekedan]] and [[Yenga Yenga]] to start his own band [[Grand Zaiko Wa Wa]].\n\n===1980-88 Departure of Pepe Manuaku and addition of Atalaku===\nFollowing the departure of [[Pepe Manuaku]], [[Roxy Tshimpaka]] (also called [[Grand Niawu]]) became as lead guitarist and [[Mbuta Matima]] became artistic director. During this period Zaiko Langa Langa released many of their most famous songs including [[Crois moi]], [[Amiti\u00e9]], [[Viya (song)|Viya]], [[Essesse]], [[LA Blonde]], [[Kamanzi]], [[Cherie Massa]], [[Lolita]], [[Kinshasa makambo]] and 1981 song of the year [[Fievre mondo]].\n\nHowever there were further internal quarrels and personnel changes with the departure in 1981 of Evoloko, Bozi Boziana and Djo Mali to form [[Langa Langa Stars]], joined a year later by Roxy Tshimpaka. By 1982 N'yoka Longo had become the effective band leader however there were also some unofficial recordings without his involvement or sanction<ref>https://www.totallyradio.com/shows/african-and-global-beat/episodes/78506</ref>.\n\nIn 1982 Zaiko introduced maracas and [[Atalaku]] ('animateur' in French or a specialist vocal typically over the 'sebene') in the band. The Atalaku firstly performed solo by [[Sonnerie]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2019}} in the critically acclaimed album [[tokangi robinet]] brought in the traditional elements into Zaiko and Congolese pop music. The mixture of maracas, African drum play by [[Djerba]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2019}} and Atalaku (traditional animation) now led by Bebe and Nono will bring huge success to the band as well as revolutionized Congolese popular music.\n\nIn 1984, [[Dindo Yogo]] arrived as a singer in the band and quickly became the group's dominant solo vocalist.\n\nDuring this period Zaiko released successful albums regularly. The band was touring Europe and Africa and was the first Zairian band to visit [[Japan]].\n\n===1988-1998 Split to Nkolo Mboka and Familia Dei===\n\nIn 1988 the band experienced another major split, between the two leaders of the group Nyoka Longo and Bimi Ombale. The band was divided in two with every musician choosing his camp between the two leaders who were part of Zaiko since its creation. With [[Meridjo]], [[Bapius]], [[Matima]], [[Zamuangana]] who were part of Zaiko from its creation staying with Nyoka Longo followed by [[Dindo Yogo]] and the band was called then [[Zaiko Langa Langa Nkolo Mboka]], to differentiate it from the band of Bimi Ombale which was called [[Zaiko Langa Langa Familia Dei]] and had [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Ilo Pablo]], [[JP Buse]] and the rest of the musicians that came in the 1980s. Zaiko Langa Langa Familia Dei dissolved in 1986<ref>http://rumbaontheriver.com/zaiko.html</ref>, after which time N'Yoka Longo's group reacquired the original name \"Zaiko Langa Langa\", which has maintained until today. N'Yoka Longo is{{when|date=March 2019}} still the leader of the group.\n\n===1999-present===\n\nIn 1999 a further split came with the dismissal of two other senior members of the band in drummer Meridjo and bassist Bapius, who went on to form the short-lived Zaiko Langa Langa Universel<ref>http://rumbaontheriver.com/zaiko.html</ref>.\n\nIn 2002, Zaiko performed in the mythic arena [[Zenith of Paris]], France. More than 6.000 fans attended. This was considered by many as the renaissance or rebirth of Zaiko. As early as 1988, Zaiko, being very popular at that time, made plan to perform in Zenith but the great split that occurred in the band stopped it for doing so.\n\nZaiko spent 6 and half years in Europe (2002\u201309). Its headquarters ware in Bruxelles, Belgium. But the band gave more concerts in France and other countries around Europe.\nDuring that time in Europe, Zaiko released three albums: Eureka (2002), Empreintes (2004), Recontres (2006). In the last album, Nyoka Longo invited many former Zaiko musicians like Malage, Beniko Popolipo; and a retired Congolese musician [[Tony Dee Bokito]]. He also recruited from Kinshasa, the son of late Dindo Yogo, [[Lola Muana]].\n\nDuring the time the Band was in Europe, Nyoka Longo, in 2006, charged Lola Muana, who was then in Kinshasa, to form a group that would promote Zaiko music in [[D.R.Congo]]. Lola recruited and formed a subsidiary group of Zaiko called [[Les Ganers de Zaiko]]. [[Bapius Muaka]], a longtime guitarist bass player who left the group during a minor split of 1999, joined the Ganers too.\n\nThe group returned in D.R.Congo in January 2009 with only five musicians: Nyoka Longo, [[Doudou Adoula]], [[Chou Lay Evoloko]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Gege Mangaya]], [[Shango Landu]] and Lola Muana. Other members of the group defected and stayed in Europe where they formed a new band named [[Les Stars de Zaiko]] under the leadership of Adamo Ekula. Couple years later, they renamed their new band [[Zaikas Kolo Mboka]].\n\nSince his recruitment in Zaiko, Lola Muana was regarded by many as the principal heir of Zaiko. But in 2009, he was forced to quit the group because of his proposal to have a valid work contract with the group. His request was denied by the President of Zaiko, N'Yoka Longo Mvula Jossart. The son of Evoloko, Shou Lay, who backed Lola's request left the group too. In November 2011, Lola Muana was reinstated in the group.\n\n==Clan Langa Langa==\nZaiko Langa Langa were both influential in their own right and through their many spin-offs. Most of these maintained a strong link to the original formation, and this is often reflected by the names they adopted. The groups that somehow belong to the Zaiko Langa Langa \"[[Franchising|franchise]]\" are collectively known as the \"Clan Langa Langa\". This includes:\n\n* [[Isifi Lokole]] (1974-1978)- [[Papa Wemba]], [[Bozi Boziana]], [[Evoloko Jocker]], [[Mavuela Somo]]\n* [[Yoka Lokole]] (1978-Pr\u00e9sent) - Papa Wemba, Bozi Boziana, Mavuela Somo\n* [[Grand Za\u00efko Wa Wa]] (1981-Pr\u00e9sent) - [[Manuaku Waku]] who was joined by successful singers like [[Shimita]], [[Djo Poster]] among others\n* [[Viva La Musica]] (1977\u20132016) - Papa Wemba, joined by [[Emeneya Mubiala]], [[Dindo Yogo]]\n* [[Tout Grand Libanko]] (1977-Pr\u00e9sent) - [[Gina Efong\u00e9]]\n* [[Choc Stars]] (1983-2019) -  Bozi Boziana, [[Tshimpaka Roxy]] joined by [[Ben Nyamabo]], [[Carlyto Lassa]], [[Defao]]\n* [[L'Orchestre Anti-Choc]] (1985-Pr\u00e9sent) - Bozi Boziana, joined by [[Deyesse Mukangi]], [[Jolie Detta]], [[Dodoli]], [[Walingonda]], [[Fifi Mofude]], etc.\n* [[Langa Langa Stars]] (1981\u20131984) - Evoloko Jocker, Bozi Boziana, Tshimpaka Roxy and [[Djo Mali]]\n* [[Za\u00efko Langa Langa Nkolo Mboka]] - [[N'Yoka Longo]], [[Meridjo]], [[Dindo Yogo]], [[Oncle Bapius]], [[Gilbert Benamayi]], [[Zamuangana]], [[Nono Monzuluku]] and [[Matima]]. They were joined by [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Adamo]], Baroza, [[Shiro Shiro]],\n* [[Za\u00efko Langa Langa Familia Dei]] (1988-1996) - [[Lengi Lenga]], [[Ilo Pablo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Beniko Popolipo]], [[Petit Poisson]], [[Djimi Yaba]]\n* [[Zaiko Universel]] (1999\u20132001)- [[Meridjo]], [[Bapius Muaka]]\n* [[Langa Langa Stars R\u00e9nov\u00e9]] (1981-Pr\u00e9sent) - Evoloko Jocker\n* [[Basilique Loningisa]] (1990-1995)- Bimi Ombale\n* [[Ngwaka Aye]] (1991-2000) - Dindo Yogo\n* [[Les Quatros de Langa Langa]], Papa Wemba, Evoloko, Bozi Boziana, Gina Efonge\n* [[Les Stars de Zaiko]], Now called [[Zaikas Kolo Mboka]] (2009-2011), Adamo Ekula, Petit Poisson, Tshanda, Papy Cocaine, etc.\n* [[Les g\u00e9ants (band)|Les g\u00e9ants]] - [[Koffi Olomide]], [[King Kester Emeneya]], [[P\u00e9p\u00e9 Kall\u00e9]], [[Sam Mangwana]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Madilu System]], [[Rigo Star]]\n* [[Les Super Stars]] - [[Endho Ndumba]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Bimi Ombale]], [[Defao]], [[Beniko Popolipo]]\n* [[Zaire All Stars]] - [[Papa Wemba]], [[Fafa De Molokai]], [[Mpongo Love]]\n* [[Les Asiatiques]] - [[Madilu System]], [[Malage de Lugendo]], [[Lassa Carlyto]]\n\n==Partial discography==\n\n;Albums\n* 1970 : ''Pauline''\n* 1972 : ''L'amoureux decu''\n* 1973 : ''Mete la v\u00e9rit\u00e9, chouchouna'', ''Mbeya Mbeya'', ''Zena''\n* 1974 : ''Liwa ya somo'', ''Mwana Wabi'', ''Mizou'', ''Eluzam'', ''Belinda ya mbongo/Onassis''\n* 1981 : ''Sarah Djenni''\n* 1983 : ''La Tout Neige'' \n* 1984 : ''Bizita'', ''Patchely''\n* 1985 : ''Zaiko Eyi Nkisi''\n* 1985 : ''Eh Ngoss! Eh Ngoss! Eh Ngoss!''\n* 1986 : ''Bongoville ''\n* 1986 : ''Pusa Kuna... Serrez! Serrez!''\n* 1997 : ''Papa Omar''\n* 1987 : ''Bongama Kamata Position''\n* 1987 : ''Subissez les cons\u00e9quences''\n* 1988 : ''Nippon Banzai au Japon''\n* 1989 : ''Jetez l'Eponge''\n* 1990 : ''Zaiko Langa-Langa F. D.''\n* 1990 : ''Ici ca va \"Fungola Motema\"\n* 1992 : ''L'Autentique Zaiko Langa Langa''\n* 1992 : ''Jamais sans nous''\n* 1993 : ''Zaire-Ghana'' (recorded in Accra in 1976, produced by [[Henri Bowane]])\n* 1994 : ''Ambiance a Kin\" (Featuring [[Adamo Ekula]], [[Baroza]], [[Malage de Lugendo]])\n* 1995 : ''Avis de recherche''\n* 1995 : ''Zekete Zekete''\n* 1996 : ''Pacha labaran''\n* 1996 : ''[[Saisie en Douane... 20 Ans D\u00e9j\u00e0]]''\n* 1997 : ''Papa Omar''\n* 1997 : ''Onassis''\n* 1997 : ''Muvaro''\n* 1997 : ''Le beau temps''\n* 1997 : ''Bongo bouger''\n* 1997 : ''Backline Lesson One''\n* 1998 : ''Sans Issue''\n* 1999 : ''Poison''\n* 2000 : ''Etumba ya la vie'' (An album by a dissident group of Meridjo: [[Zaiko Universel]])\n* 2001 : ''Legend''\n* 2001 : ''Feeling''\n* 2002 : ''Anthologie''\n* 2003 : ''Sentiment Awa / Essesse\n* 2003 : ''Eureka!''\n* 2004 : ''[[Empreinte]]''\n* 2006 : ''Rencontres''\n* 2011 : ''Bande Annonce''\n\n;Contributing artist\n* 1994 : ''[[The Rough Guide to World Music]]''\n\n==References==\n*[http://kenyapage.net/music/zaiko.html Africa Music Centre]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.zaikolangalanga.com Official Zaiko Langa Langa homepage]\n*[http://www.documen.tv/asset/Zaiko_Langa_Langa.html \" Zaiko Langa Langa \"]  1999 Documentary 52'\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Tholme", "label": "safe", "comment": "lintfix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Za%C3%AFko_Langa_Langa"}
{"title_page": "Prahasta", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox epic character\n| series = [[Ramayana]]\n| relatives = father: [[Sumali]],\nmother: [[Ketumati]],\nsister: [[Kaikesi]]\n}}\n\nIn the [[Hindu]] epic the ''[[Ramayana]]'', '''Prahasta''' ([[Sanskrit]]: \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0939\u0938\u094d\u0924, [[IAST]]: prahasta, lit. ''he who has extended hands'') was a powerful [[rakshasa]] warrior,  chief commander of [[Ravana]]'s army of [[Lanka]]. In his next birth Prahastha was reborn as [[Purochana]] in the [[Mahabharata]] as [[Duryodhana]]'s trusted aide and who was responsible for the [[Lakshagraha]] incident.\n\n==Legend==\nPrahastha leads Ravana's army in the wars against [[Yama (Hinduism)|Yama]], [[Kubera]] and the [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]], and the [[Asuras]] and [[Daityas]], through which Ravana establishes his sovereignty over the three worlds. He also leads the initial Lankan response to the invasion led by [[Rama]], [[Lakshmana]], [[Sugriva]] and the [[Vanara]] army.{{cn|date=January 2017}}\n\nPrahastha was not only the commander-in-chief,  he was also the brother of [[Kaikesi]],thus making him [[Ravana]]\u2019s maternal uncle.{{cn|date=January 2017}}\n\nPrahastha killed several important warriors of Sugriva's army and was actually proving to be a real threat to the army of Rama. As per one version of Ramayana, Prahastha was killed by laxman. And in another version, [[Nila (Ramayana)|Nila]] hurled a rock at Prahastha that broke his neck and killed him. (Valmiki Ramayana, book 6, canto 58, verses 53,54)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valmikiramayan.net/yuddha/sarga58/utf8/yuddha_58_frame.htm|title=Valmiki Ramayana - Yuddha Kanda - Sarga 58|last=Rao|first=Desiraju Hanumanta|date=|website=www.valmikiramayan.net|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-02}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Ramesh Menon]] (2001), ''The Ramayana''.\n\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* http://www.valmikiramayan.net/yuddha/sarga57/yuddha_57_prose.htm\n* http://ancientvoice.wikidot.com/vrm:prahasta\n\n[[Category:Rakshasa in the Ramayana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox epic character\n| series = [[Ramayana]]\n| relatives = father: [[Sumali]],\nmother: [[Ketumati]],\nsister: [[Kaikesi]]\n}}\n\nIn the [[Hindu]] epic the ''[[Ramayana]]'', '''Prahasta''' ([[Sanskrit]]: \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0939\u0938\u094d\u0924, [[IAST]]: prahasta, lit. ''he who has extended hands'') was a powerful [[rakshasa]] warrior,  chief commander of [[Ravana]]'s army of [[Lanka]]. In his next birth Prahastha was reborn as [[Purochana]] in the [[Mahabharata]] as [[Duryodhana]]'s trusted aide and who was responsible for the [[Lakshagraha]] incident.\n\n==Legend==\nPrahastha leads Ravana's army in the wars against [[Yama (Hinduism)|Yama]], [[Kubera]] and the [[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]], and the [[Asuras]] and [[Daityas]], through which Ravana establishes his sovereignty over the three worlds. He also leads the initial Lankan response to the invasion led by [[Rama]], [[Lakshmana]], [[Sugriva]] and the [[Vanara]] army.{{cn|date=January 2017}}\n\nPrahastha was not only the commander-in-chief,  he was also the brother of [[Kaikesi]],thus making him [[Ravana]]\u2019s maternal uncle.{{cn|date=January 2017}}\n\nPrahastha killed several important warriors of Sugriva's army and was actually proving to be a real threat to the army of Rama. As per Valmiki Ramayana, Prahastha was killed by laxman. Nila hurled a rock at Prahastha that broke his neck and killed him. (Valmiki Ramayana, book 6, canto 58, verses 53,54)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valmikiramayan.net/yuddha/sarga58/utf8/yuddha_58_frame.htm|title=Valmiki Ramayana - Yuddha Kanda - Sarga 58|last=Rao|first=Desiraju Hanumanta|date=|website=www.valmikiramayan.net|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-02}}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Ramesh Menon]] (2001), ''The Ramayana''.\n\n{{Ramayana}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* http://www.valmikiramayan.net/yuddha/sarga57/yuddha_57_prose.htm\n* http://ancientvoice.wikidot.com/vrm:prahasta\n\n[[Category:Rakshasa in the Ramayana]]\n", "name_user": "Crazyranga", "label": "safe", "comment": "gnome edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prahasta"}
{"title_page": "Daisuke", "text_new": "{{Infobox Given Name Revised\n| name = Daisuke\n| pronunciation= D\u00e1-\u00ed-s(\u00fa)-k\u00e9\n| gender = Daddy big pp\n| meaning = different meanings depending on the [[kanji]] used\n| region = Japan\n| origin = Japanese\n| related names = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Daisuke'''|\u3060\u3044\u3059\u3051, \u30c0\u30a4\u30b9\u30b1}} is a common masculine Japanese given name.\n\n==Possible writings==\nDaisuke can be written using different [[kanji]] characters and can mean:\n*\u5927\u8f14, \"big, help\"\n*\u5927\u4ecb, \"big, mediate\"\n*\u5927\u7950, \"big, help\"\n*\u5927\u52a9, \"big, help\"\n*\u5927\u5178, \"big, law/rule/ceremony\"\nThe name can also be written in [[hiragana]] or [[katakana]].\n\n==Manga artists==\n*[[Daisuke Higuchi]] (\u6a0b\u53e3 \u5927\u8f14), a Japanese female manga artist best known for her work on ''[[Whistle!]]''\n*[[Daisuke Igarashi]] (\u4e94\u5341\u5d50\u5927\u4ecb), a Japanese manga artist known for his bold, detailed art style and innovative storytelling\n*[[Daisuke Moriyama]] (\u68ee\u5c71\u5927\u8f14), a Japanese manga artist best known for creating the ''[[Chrono Crusade]]'' series\n\n==Sportspeople==\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Arakawa]]|\u8352\u5ddd \u5927\u8f14||born 1981}}, Japanese long jumper\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Ejima]]|\u6c5f\u5cf6 \u5927\u4f51}}, Japanese Paralympic swimmer\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Houki]]|\u5b9d\u4e80 \u5927\u8f14||born 1961}}, Japanese water polo player\n*[[Daisuke Ikeshima]] (\u6c60\u5cf6 \u5927\u4ecb), retired Japanese race walker\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Maeda]]|\u524d\u7530 \u5927\u4ecb}}, Japanese Paralympic swimmer\n*[[Daisuke Matsuzaka]] (\u677e\u5742 \u5927\u8f14), Japanese professional baseball player who pitches for the [[Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks]]\n*[[Daisuke Murakami (snowboarder)]], (\u6751\u4e0a \u5927\u8f14), Japanese snowboarder who competed in the [[2002 Winter Olympics]]\n*[[Daisuke Naito]] (\u5185\u85e4 \u5927\u52a9), retired Japanese professional boxer\n*[[Daisuke Nakata]] (\u4e2d\u7530\u5927\u8f14), Japanese trampolinist who competed in the [[2000 Summer Olympics]]\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Obara]]|\u5c0f\u539f \u5927\u8f14||born 1981}}, Japanese ice hockey player\n*[[Daisuke Ohata]], (\u5927\u7551\u5927\u4ecb), Japanese rugby player\n*[[Daisuke Usami]], (\u5b87\u4f50\u7f8e \u5927\u8f14), Japanese volleyball player\n\n===Football players===\n*[[Daisuke Ichikawa]] (\u5e02\u5ddd \u5927\u7950), Japanese football player who plays as a defender and midfielder for the [[Fujieda MYFC]] team\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Ishizu]]|\u77f3\u6d25 \u5927\u4ecb||born 1990}}, Japanese football player\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Kanzaki]]|\u795e\u5d0e \u5927\u8f14||born 1985}}, Japanese footballer\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Kikuchi]]|\u83ca\u6c60 \u5927\u4ecb||born 1991}}, Japanese footballer\n*[[Daisuke Matsui]] (\u677e\u4e95 \u5927\u8f14), Japanese footballer who plays for [[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] of [[Ekstraklasa]] in Poland\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Nakamori]]|\u4e2d\u68ee \u5927\u4ecb||born 1974}}, Japanese footballer and manager\n*[[Daisuke Nasu]] (\u90a3\u9808 \u5927\u4eae), Japanese football player who plays for the [[Urawa Red Diamonds]]\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Nishiguchi]]|\u897f\u53e3 \u5927\u8f14||born 1988}}, Japanese footballer\n*[[Daisuke Oku]], Japanese former football player \n*[[Daisuke Sakata]], (\u5742\u7530 \u5927\u8f14), Japanese football (soccer) player who plays for [[Avispa Fukuoka]] in the [[J. League]]\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Tanaka]]|\u7530\u4e2d \u5927\u8f14||born 1983}}, Japanese footballer\n\n===Skaters===\n*[[Daisuke Murakami (figure skater)]] (\u6751\u4e0a \u5927\u4ecb), Japanese figure skater\n*[[Daisuke Takahashi]], figure skater (\u9ad9\u6a4b \u5927\u8f14), Japanese figure skater\n\n===Wrestlers===\n*[[Daisuke Harada]] (\u539f\u7530 \u5927\u8f14), professional wrestler signed to [[Pro Wrestling Noah]]\n*[[Daisuke Ikeda]] (\u6c60\u7530\u5927\u8f14), professional wrestler competing in the [[Independent circuit]] in Japan\n*[[Daisuke Sasaki]] (\u4f50\u3005\u6728 \u5927\u8f14), professional wrestler\n*[[Daisuke Sekimoto]] (\u95a2\u672c \u5927\u4ecb), professional wrestler\n*[[Daisuke Tochiazuma]], retired sumo wrestler\n\n==Voice actors==\n*[[Daisuke G\u014dri]] (\u90f7\u91cc \u5927\u8f14, 1952-2010), Japanese voice actor, narrator and actor\n*[[Daisuke Hirakawa]] (\u5e73\u5ddd \u5927\u8f14), Japanese voice actor\n*[[Daisuke Kishio]] (\u5cb8\u5c3e \u3060\u3044\u3059\u3051), Japanese voice actor\n*[[Daisuke Matsubara]] (\u677e\u539f \u5927\u5178), Japanese voice actor\n*[[Daisuke Nakamura]] (\u4e2d\u6751 \u592a\u4eae), Japanese voice actor\n*[[Daisuke Namikawa]] (\u6d6a\u5ddd \u5927\u8f14), Japanese voice actor\n*[[Daisuke Ono]] (\u5c0f\u91ce \u5927\u8f14), Japanese voice actor well known for voicing [[List_of_Black_Butler_characters#Sebastian Michaelis|Sebastian Michaelis]] in the anime adaption of [[Black Butler]]\n*[[Daisuke Sakaguchi]] (\u962a\u53e3 \u5927\u52a9), Japanese voice actor affiliated with [[Aoni Production]]\n\n==Other==\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Amaya]]|\u5929\u8c37 \u5927\u8f14||born 1977}}, Japanese independent game developer\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Asakura]]|\u6d45\u5009 \u5927\u4ecb||born 1967}}, Japanese pop artist, songwriter and producer \n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Ban]]|\u4f34 \u5927\u4ecb||born 1967}}, Japanese actor\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Enomoto]]|\u698e\u672c \u5927\u8f14||born 1971}}, Japanese businessman and former livedoor executive \n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Inoue]]|\u4e95\u4e0a \u5927\u4f51||born 1940}}, Japanese businessman who invented [[Karaoke]]\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Ishiwatari]]|\u77f3\u6e21 \u592a\u8f14||born 1973}}, Japanese video game developer and musician\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Katagami]]|\u7247\u4e0a \u5927\u8f14||born 1986}}, Japanese shogi player\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Kat\u014d]]|\u52a0\u6771 \u5927\u4ecb||1911\u20131975}}, Japanese actor\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuke Kobayashi]]|\u5c0f\u6797 \u5927\u7950||born 1987}}, Japanese basketball player\n*{{Nihongo|[[Daisuk