te=November 2, 2015 }} City of Hartford \u2013 Court of Common Council</ref><ref>[http://www.hartford.gov/council/contact-council-members] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922011425/http://www.hartford.gov/council/contact-council-members |date=September 22, 2018 }} City of Hartford \u2013 Court of Common Council \u2013 Contact</ref>\n|-\n! Name !!Position!! Political affiliation\n|-\n| Maly Rosado ||[[Chairwoman|President]]|| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| T.J. Clarke ||[[Majority Leader]]|| Democratic\n|-\n| James B. Sanchez ||Councilman|| Democratic\n|-\n| Nick Lebron ||Councilman|| Democratic\n|-\n| Marilyn E. Rossetti ||Councilwoman||Democratic\n|-\n| Shirley Surgeon ||Councilwoman|| Democratic\n|-\n| John Q. Gale  ||Councilman|| Hartford Party\n|-\n| Wildaliz Bermudez ||[[Minority Leader]]||[[Working Families Party|Working Families]]\n|-\n| Joshua Michtom ||Councilman|| Working Families\n|}\n\n===Emergency services===\n[[File:Engine Co 1 Fire Station Hartford CT.JPG|thumb|Engine Co. 1 Fire Station]]\nThe [[Hartford Fire Department]] provides fire protection and first responder emergency medical services to the city of Hartford, operating out of 12 fire stations located throughout the city. It is the fifth-largest fire department in Connecticut and maintains a fire apparatus fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartford.gov/fire/|title=Hartford.Gov \u2013 Hartford Fire Department|access-date=July 26, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720002324/http://www.hartford.gov/fire/|archive-date=July 20, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartford.gov/about-hfd|title=Hartford.Gov \u2013 About HFD|access-date=April 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903032911/http://www.hartford.gov/about-hfd|archive-date=September 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hartford Police Department was founded in 1860, though the history of law enforcement in Hartford begins in 1636.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hartford.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2448|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313041231/http://www.hartford.gov/police/HistoryFolder/2008HistoryPage.htm|url-status=dead|title=Hartford.Gov \u2013 Department of Families, Children, Youth and Recreation|archivedate=March 13, 2008|website=hartford.gov}}</ref> It is located at 253 High Street and includes divisions such as animal control, bomb squad, and detective bureau.\n\nHartford outsources ambulance services to private companies, including Aetna Ambulance in the [[Neighborhoods of Hartford, Connecticut#South End|South End]] and [[American Medical Response]] in the [[Neighborhoods of Hartford, Connecticut#North End|North End]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bordobaro|first1=Gregory|title=CT's ambulance services fragmented, consolidated|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20130722/PRINTEDITION/307189922|accessdate=April 5, 2015|work=Hartford Business Journal|date=July 22, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412210050/http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20130722/PRINTEDITION/307189922|archive-date=April 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Club\n! scope=\"col\" | League, Sport\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" | Titles\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Yard Goats]]\n| [[Eastern League (baseball)|EL]], Baseball\n| [[Dunkin' Donuts Park]]\n| 1973\n| 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Wolf Pack]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]], Ice hockey\n| [[XL Center]]\n| 1926\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Athletic]]\n| [[USL Championship|USLC]], Soccer\n| [[Dillon Stadium]]\n| 2019\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | Hartford Wanderers\n| [[USA Rugby]], Rugby Union\n| [[Colt Park]]\n| 1966\n| 0\n|}\n\nThe [[Hartford Wolf Pack]] of the [[American Hockey League]] plays [[ice hockey]] at the [[XL Center]] in downtown Hartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordwolfpack.com/|title=Hartford Wolf Pack|last=Pack|first=Hartford Wolf|website=hartfordwolfpack.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520111607/http://www.hartfordwolfpack.com/|archive-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The XL Center also hosts larger-profile games for both the men's and women's basketball teams of the [[Connecticut Huskies|UConn Huskies]]. Other UConn home games are played at [[Gampel Pavilion]] located on the university's campus in [[Storrs, CT|Storrs]]. In addition, all [[Connecticut Huskies|UConn Huskies]] Men's Ice Hockey home games are played at the XL Center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/sports/hockey/hc-uconn-hockey-east-arena-site-1025-20151024-story.html|title=UConn's Success at XL Puts On-Campus Arena Focus On Freitas Upgrade|first=JENNY|last=WILSON|website=courant.com|access-date=February 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224002434/https://www.courant.com/sports/hockey/hc-uconn-hockey-east-arena-site-1025-20151024-story.html|archive-date=February 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hartford Yard Goats]], the Double-A affiliate of the [[Colorado Rockies]], moved to Hartford in 2017, moving from [[New Britain, Connecticut|New Britain]]. The team currently play at [[Dunkin' Donuts Park]].\n\nAs of 2019, Hartford is home to a [[United Soccer League|USL]] team, playing in the 5,500 seat [[Dillon Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/906108|title=Hartford Council Approves Dillon Stadium Deal|date=April 9, 2018|work=United Soccer League|access-date=May 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511215618/https://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/906108|archive-date=May 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Former teams===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Club\n! scope=\"col\" | League, Sport\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" | Folded/Moved\n! scope=\"col\" | Titles\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Whalers|New England/Hartford Whalers]]\n| [[World Hockey Association|WHA]], [[National Hockey League|NHL]], Hockey\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1975\n| 1997 (Moved to North Carolina)\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Dark Blues]]\n| [[National League|NL]], Baseball\n| [[Hartford Ball Club Grounds]]\n| 1874\n| 1876 (founding member of the National League)\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Chiefs]]\n| [[Eastern League (baseball)|EL]], Baseball\n| [[Morgan G. Bulkeley Stadium|Bulkeley Stadium]]\n| 1938\n| 1952\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Boston Celtics]]\n| [[National Basketball Association|NBA]], Basketball\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1975\n| 1995 (Part-time)\n| 17\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Connecticut Pride|Hartford Hellcats/Connecticut Pride]]\n| [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]], Basketball\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1993\n| 2000\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[New England Blizzard]]\n| [[American Basketball League (1996\u201398)|ABL]], Basketball\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1996\n| 1998\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Blues]]\n| [[National Football League|NFL]], Football\n| [[East Hartford Velodrome]]\n| 1925\n| 1927\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Colonials]]\n| [[United Football League (2009\u20132012)|UFL]], Football\n| [[Pratt & Whitney Stadium at Rentschler Field|Rentschler Field]]\n| 2010\n| 2010\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Connecticut Coyotes]]\n| [[Arena Football League|AFL]], Football\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1995\n| 1996\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[New England Sea Wolves]]\n| [[Arena Football League|AFL]], Football\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1999\n| 2000\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Connecticut Bicentennials|Hartford Bicentennials]]\n| [[North American Soccer League (1968\u201384)|NASL]], Soccer\n| [[Dillon Stadium]]\n| 1975\n| 1976\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford Hellions]]\n| [[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u201392)|MISL]], Soccer\n| [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n| 1979\n| 1981\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Hartford FoxForce]]\n| [[World TeamTennis]], Tennis\n| [[State Arsenal and Armory]]\n| 2000\n| 2006\n| 0\n|}\n\nHartford became the home of the WHA's New England Whalers in 1975 after the club moved from Boston, one of four WHA teams that joined the NHL in 1979. The city was home to the [[NHL]]'s [[Hartford Whalers]] from 1979 to 1997, before the team relocated to [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] and became the [[Carolina Hurricanes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordwhalers.org/history.htm|title=The Blowhole \u2013 Hartford/New England Whalers History|website=hartfordwhalers.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015203342/http://www.hartfordwhalers.org/history.htm|archive-date=October 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Boston Celtics]] played various home games per year in Hartford from 1975 until 1995, when they opened the new [[TD Garden]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/1995-04-15/sports/9504150302_1_civic-center-celtics-general-manager-celtics-move|title=Civic Center Farewell For Celtics?|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHartford was also home to the Hartford Hellions of the Major Indoor Soccer League (MISL).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/sports/hc-pictures-defunct-connecticut-sports-teams-012-photo.html|title=Hartford Hellions|last=Handout|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHartford formerly had a [[National League]] [[baseball team]], the [[Hartford Dark Blues]], in the 1870s, and had an [[NFL]] team, the [[Hartford Blues]], for three seasons in the 1920s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/sports/hc-pictures-defunct-connecticut-sports-teams-001-photo.html|title=Hartford Blues|last=Handout|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519040321/http://www.courant.com/sports/hc-pictures-defunct-connecticut-sports-teams-001-photo.html|archive-date=May 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHartford briefly had a team in the [[United Football League (2009\u20132012)|UFL]] called the [[Hartford Colonials]], but games were played in neighboring [[East Hartford, Connecticut|East Hartford's]] [[Rentschler Field Stadium|Rentschler Field]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-06-22/sports/hc-colonials-owner-hartford-0623-20110622_1_ufl-officials-hartford-colonials-nfl-lockout|title=Hartford Colonials Calling Rentschler Field Home Again|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|access-date=May 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129000143/http://articles.courant.com/2011-06-22/sports/hc-colonials-owner-hartford-0623-20110622_1_ufl-officials-hartford-colonials-nfl-lockout|archive-date=January 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2006 Hartford was home to the [[Hartford FoxForce]] of [[World TeamTennis]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bailer |first1=Darice |title=Team Tennis Finds a Home in Hartford |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/23/nyregion/team-tennis-finds-a-home-in-hartford.html?searchResultPosition=19 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Highways===\n[[File:Bulkeley Bridge, Hartford.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bulkeley Bridge]] over the Connecticut River]][[File:2019 08 SX530 023.jpg|thumb|2019 08 SX530 023]]\n\n[[Interstate 84 in Connecticut|I-84]] which runs from [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], to its intersection with [[Interstate 90 in Massachusetts|I-90]] in [[Sturbridge, Massachusetts|Sturbridge]], just over the Massachusetts border, and [[Interstate 91 in Connecticut|I-91]], which runs from [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]] along the Connecticut River ultimately to Canada, intersect in downtown Hartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://connecticuthistory.org/the-interstate-highway-system-comes-to-hartford/|title=The Interstate Highway System Comes to Hartford {{!}} ConnecticutHistory.org|website=connecticuthistory.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201211823/http://connecticuthistory.org/the-interstate-highway-system-comes-to-hartford/|archive-date=February 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to I-84 and I-91, two other highways service the city: [[Connecticut Route 2|Route 2]], an expressway that runs from downtown Hartford to [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]], passing through [[Norwich, Connecticut|Norwich]] and past [[Foxwoods Resort Casino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycroads.com/roads/CT-2/|title=CT 2 Expressway|website=nycroads.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129082045/http://www.nycroads.com/roads/CT-2/|archive-date=November 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Wilbur Cross Highway]] portion of [[Connecticut Route 15|Route 15]] that skirts the southeastern part of the city near Brainard Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-84_MA/|title=Wilbur Cross Highway (I-84)|website=bostonroads.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215000446/http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/I-84_MA/|archive-date=December 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A short connector known as the [[Conlin\u2013Whitehead Highway]] also provides direct access from I-91 to the Capitol Area of downtown Hartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/i484.html|title=Connecticut I-484|last=Oglesby|first=Scott|website=kurumi.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809164833/http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/i484.html|archive-date=August 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Main St. Bridge is a historic bridge on the highway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.past-inc.org/historic-bridges/stone-mainst.html|title=Main Street Bridge|website=past-inc.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630180627/http://www.past-inc.org/historic-bridges/stone-mainst.html|archive-date=June 30, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHartford experiences heavy traffic as a result of its substantial suburban population (nearly 10 times that of the actual city). As a result, thousands of people travel on area highways at the start and end of each workday. I-84 experiences traffic from [[Farmington, Connecticut|Farmington]] through Hartford and into [[East Hartford, Connecticut|East Hartford]] and [[Manchester, Connecticut|Manchester]] during the [[rush hour]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://connecticut.cbslocal.com/traffic/|title=Traffic|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606053310/http://connecticut.cbslocal.com/traffic/|archive-date=June 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/50-worst-commutes-americas-highways-to-hell|title=50 Worst Commutes: America's Highways to Hell|last=Beast|first=The Daily|date=January 30, 2017|website=The Daily Beast|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605072429/http://www.thedailybeast.com/50-worst-commutes-americas-highways-to-hell|archive-date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Charter Oak Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|[[Charter Oak Bridge]] over the Connecticut River]]\nSeveral major surface arteries also run through the city. Albany Avenue\n([[U.S. Route 44 in Connecticut|Route 44]]) runs westward through the northern part of [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]] to the [[Farmington Valley]] and the hills of northern [[Litchfield County]] and into New York, and eastward towards [[Putnam, Connecticut|Putnam]] and into [[Rhode Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/us44.html|title=Connecticut US 44|last=Oglesby|first=Scott|website=kurumi.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911071704/http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/us44.html|archive-date=September 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Blue Hills Avenue ([[Route 187 (Connecticut \u2013 Massachusetts)|Route 187]]) runs north from Albany Avenue toward [[Bloomfield, Connecticut|Bloomfield]] and [[East Granby, Connecticut|East Granby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/ct187.html|title=Connecticut Route 187|last=Oglesby|first=Scott|website=kurumi.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708213452/http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/ct187.html|archive-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Main Street ([[Connecticut Route 159|Route 159]]) heads north through [[Windsor, Connecticut|Windsor]] towards the western suburbs of [[Springfield, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/ct159.html|title=Connecticut Route 159|last=Oglesby|first=Scott|website=kurumi.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709032159/http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/ct159.html|archive-date=July 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Wethersfield Avenue ([[Connecticut Route 99|Route 99]]) heads south through [[Wethersfield, Connecticut|Wethersfield]] towards [[Middletown, Connecticut|Middletown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/ct99.html|title=Connecticut Route 99|last=Oglesby|first=Scott|website=kurumi.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812190415/http://www.kurumi.com/roads/ct/ct99.html|archive-date=August 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Maple Avenue heads south-southwest, becoming the [[Berlin Turnpike]] in Wethersfield and [[Newington, Connecticut|Newington]]. Farmington Avenue heads west through West Hartford Center and [[Farmington, Connecticut|Farmington]] towards [[Torrington, Connecticut|Torrington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/ecd/cwp/view.asp?a=1106&Q=250996|title=DECD: Connecticut maps|last=Office|first=Enter your Company or Top-Level|website=ct.gov|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605044150/http://www.ct.gov/ecd/cwp/view.asp?A=1106&Q=250996|archive-date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Interstate 84 in Connecticut#Future|label 1=I-84 Hartford}}\n\nA large-scale project is being planned to rebuild the I-84 viaduct that cross through the city along with moving I-91 away from the Connecticut River.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.i84hartford.com/|title=I-84 Hartford Project|website=i84hartford.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521192118/http://i84hartford.com/|archive-date=May 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-i-84-public-advisory-committee-meets-20180906-story.html|title=Planners See Trouble Ahead For Larson's Plan For Highway Tunnel Beneath Hartford|last=Gosselin|first=Kenneth R.|work=courant.com|access-date=October 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010213735/http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-i-84-public-advisory-committee-meets-20180906-story.html|archive-date=October 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Rail===\n{{See also|Union Station (Hartford)|Hartford Line}}\n[[File:HartfordUnionStation.jpg|thumb|right|Hartford's [[Union Station (Hartford)|Union Station]]]]\n[[Amtrak]] provides service from Hartford to [[Vermont]] via Springfield and southward to [[New Haven]]. The station also serves numerous bus companies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Contrada|first1=Fred|title=First passenger train in a generation stops at Northampton as new Amtrak service begins|url=http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2014/12/first_passenger_train_in_a_gen.html|accessdate=December 5, 2015|agency=MassLive.com|date=December 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208061328/http://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2014/12/first_passenger_train_in_a_gen.html|archive-date=December 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHartford Union Station is also served by the [[Hartford Line]], a commuter rail service that runs between New Haven and Springfield and stops at stations in communities along [[Interstate 91]]. It uses the rail line owned by Amtrak.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stacom|first1=Dan|title=Springfield-To-New Haven Commuter Rail Cost Increases, Service Begins in 2018|url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-amtrak-hartford-line-1204-20151204-story.html|accessdate=December 5, 2015|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=December 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205114423/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-amtrak-hartford-line-1204-20151204-story.html|archive-date=December 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"CTrail\" branded trains provide service along the corridor, and riders can use Hartford Line tickets to travel on board most Amtrak trains along the corridor at the same prices. The service launched on June 16, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/expo/news/erry-2018/06/7a3d72699a8717/ctrail.html |title=Hundreds head to Hartford to celebrate new Springfield-to-New Haven CTrail line: 9 takeaways from the launch |website=MassLive |last=Kinney |first=Jim |date=June 17, 2018 |access-date=June 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616115221/https://www.masslive.com/expo/news/erry-2018/06/7a3d72699a8717/ctrail.html |archive-date=June 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-hartford-line-opens-20180615-story.html |title=Thousands Take A Free Ride On Hartford Line's Inaugural Run |last=Porter |first=Mikaela |last2=Owens |first2=David |date=June 17, 2018 |access-date=June 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617014027/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-hartford-line-opens-20180615-story.html |archive-date=June 17, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-ctrail-ribbon-cutting-hartford-new-haven-20180614-story.html |title=Connecticut, Massachusetts Officials Cut Ribbon On Hartford Line |last=Rondinone |first=Nicholas |date=June 15, 2018 |website=Hartford Courant |access-date=June 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616222625/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-ctrail-ribbon-cutting-hartford-new-haven-20180614-story.html |archive-date=June 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Airports===\n[[File:Florida 148.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bradley International Airport]]]]\n[[Bradley International Airport]] (BDL) is located in [[Windsor Locks, Connecticut]] and offers more than 150 daily departures to over 30 destinations on 9 airlines. [[Connecticut Transit]] provides bus service between Bradley International Airport and downtown Hartford. Other airports serving the Hartford area include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bradleyairport.com/Flights/destinations.aspx |title=Destinations |publisher=Bradleyairport.com |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=June 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604083658/http://www.bradleyairport.com/Flights/destinations.aspx |archivedate=June 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n*[[Hartford-Brainard Airport]] (HFD), located in Hartford off [[Interstate 91|I-91]] and close to Wethersfield; serves charter and local flights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=HFD|title=AirportIQ 5010|website=gcr1.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303171554/http://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=HFD|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Westover Metropolitan Airport]] (CEF), located in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts]], {{convert|27|mi|km}} north of Hartford; serves commercial, local, charter, and military flights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=CEF|title=AirportIQ 5010|website=gcr1.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215741/http://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=CEF|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Tweed New Haven Regional Airport]] (HVN), located in New Haven; serves [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=HVN|title=AirportIQ 5010|website=gcr1.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175919/http://www.gcr1.com/5010web/airport.cfm?Site=HVN|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\n[[Connecticut Transit]] (CTtransit) is owned by the [[Connecticut Department of Transportation]]. The Hartford Division of CTtransit operates local and commuter bus service within the city and the surrounding area. Hartford's Downtown Area Shuttle (DASH) bus route is a free downtown circulator. All city buses are equipped with bike racks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cttransit.com/RoutesSchedules/Display.asp?DivID={7428A88D-DDD7-4910-9C2F-AD1E63B94375} |title=Hartford Routes & Schedules |publisher=CT Transit |accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, [[CTfastrak]], Connecticut's first [[bus rapid transit]] system, opened, providing a separated right-of-way between Hartford and [[New Britain, Connecticut|New Britain]]. In addition, express bus services travel from downtown Hartford and Waterbury, servicing intermediate suburban communities like [[Southington, Connecticut|Southington]] and [[Cheshire, Connecticut|Cheshire]], providing reliable public transportation between these communities for the first time. CTfastrak consists of 10 stations along the dedicated New Britain to Hartford busway, as well as a downtown loop serving [[Union Station (Hartford)|Union Station]] and other downtown landmarks. Amenities include high-level station platforms, on-board wi-fi, ticket machines for pre-boarding fare collection, and real-time arrival information at stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cttransit.com/schedules|title=Schedules {{!}} CTtransit \u2013 Connecticut DOT-owned bus service|website=www.cttransit.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601230134/https://www.cttransit.com/schedules|archive-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cttransit.com/sites/default/files/maps/division/ctfastrak_system_DEC2016.pdf|title=CTFASTRAK SYSTEM MAP|date=December 2016|website=Connecticut Transit|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425183909/https://www.cttransit.com/sites/default/files/maps/division/ctfastrak_system_DEC2016.pdf|archive-date=April 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nInterstate bus service is provided by [[Peter Pan Bus Lines|Peter Pan Bus]], [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound Bus]] and [[Megabus (North America)|Megabus]]. [[Chinatown bus lines]] provide low-cost bus service between Hartford and their New York and Boston hubs. In addition, there are buses for connections to smaller cities in the state. The main bus station is located on the ground floor of the transport center at Hartford Union Station at One Union Place, serving [[Peter Pan Bus Lines|Peter Pan Bus]] and [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound Bus]] customers. All [[Megabus (North America)|Megabus]] arrivals and departures are at the corner of Columbus Boulevard and Talcott Street on the opposite side of downtown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://locations.greyhound.com/bus-stations/us/connecticut/hartford/bus-station-60060|title=Hartford Connecticut Bus Station {{!}} Greyhound|website=locations.greyhound.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516060818/http://locations.greyhound.com/bus-stations/us/connecticut/hartford/bus-station-60060|archive-date=May 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://peterpanbus.com/locations/connecticut/hartford/|title=Hartford|work=Peter Pan Bus Lines|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426075819/https://peterpanbus.com/locations/connecticut/hartford/|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Bicycle===\nA bicycle route runs through the center of Hartford. This route is a small piece of the large eastern bicycle route \u2013 the [[East Coast Greenway]] (ECG). The {{convert|3000|mi|km|adj=on}} ECG runs from [[Calais, Maine]] to the [[Florida Keys]]. The route is intended to be off-road, but some sections are currently on-road. The section through Hartford is right through the middle of Bushnell Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riverfront.org/parks/walkways-trails|title=Walkways & Trails {{!}} Riverfront Recapture|website=www.riverfront.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517221131/http://www.riverfront.org/parks/walkways-trails|archive-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greenway.org/pdf/CT.pdf|title=East Coast Greenway|year=2010|website=greenway.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129105251/http://www.greenway.org/pdf/CT.pdf|archive-date=January 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/bike-paths-connecticut-100706.html|title=Bike Paths in Connecticut|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911150730/http://traveltips.usatoday.com/bike-paths-connecticut-100706.html|archive-date=September 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are designated bicycle lanes on several roads including Capitol Avenue, Zion Street, Scarborough Lane, Whitney, and South Whitney.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/hc-ct-bike-safety-laws-20150601-story.html|title=Bike Advocates Say Newly Passed Reforms Long Overdue|last=HLADKY|first=GREGORY B.|work=courant.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119072539/http://www.courant.com/politics/hc-ct-bike-safety-laws-20150601-story.html|archive-date=November 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA bike share program from [[LimeBike]] that allows riders to find a GPS-tracked bike, unlock it and pay $1 per half-hour of ride time began in Hartford in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-hartford-bike-share-20180122-story.html|title=Bike Share Startup Coming to Hartford This Spring|last=ORMSETH|first=MATTHEW|work=courant.com|access-date=January 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201020617/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-hartford-bike-share-20180122-story.html|archive-date=February 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The bike share program enabled more than five thousand rides in the first week of the program.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allan Brooks |first1=Spencer |title=LimeBike: 5,000+ rides in Hartford's first week |url=http://fox61.com/2018/06/14/limebike-5000-rides-in-hartfords-first-week/ |website=fox61.com |publisher=Fox 61 |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626054604/http://fox61.com/2018/06/14/limebike-5000-rides-in-hartfords-first-week/ |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Cuisine===\n\nThe first American Cookbook was ''American Cookery, The Art of Dressing Viands, Fish, Poultry, and Vegetables'' by Amelia Simons, published in Hartford by Hudson & Goodwin in 1796. It was also the first cookbook to include recipes for squash and cornmeal, and it contained the first published recipe for pumpkin pie. It influenced a generation of American baking with a recipe for leavening bread with pearl ash.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Huget |first1=Jennifer |title=America's First Cookbook |journal=Hog River Journal |date=Spring 2006}}</ref> The full text of the book is available online.<ref name=\"Archive.org\">{{cite web |title=Full text of \"American Cookery: The Art of Dressing Viands, Fish, Poultry, and Vegetables\" |url=https://archive.org/stream/americancookery12815gut/12815.txt |website=Archive.org |publisher=Archive.org |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211162521/http://archive.org/stream/americancookery12815gut/12815.txt |archive-date=December 11, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHartford's cuisine was shaped by its early settlers, who brought Dutch and English influence which combined with that of the [[Saukiog]] Indians in the area.<ref name=\"Archive.org\" /> The first half of the 20th century brought significant Polish immigration and a number of Polish restaurants, some of which still operate today.<ref>{{cite web |title=HISTORY, TRADITION, CULTURE |url=http://polishhomect.org/history-tradition-culture/ |website=polishnationalhomect.org |publisher=The Polish National Home of Hartford |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627062310/http://polishhomect.org/history-tradition-culture/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the other hand, Italian food wasn't always accepted; a long-time Hartford restaurant owner recollected that, \"in 1938, you wouldn't put an Italian name on a restaurant sign because everyone would think you were associated with the Mafia.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cohn |first1=Lindsay |title=Made in Connecticut: Flavors only found in Hartford |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/experience/food-and-wine/2017/02/27/made-connecticut-flavors-only-found-hartford/98263356/ |work=USA Today |access-date=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626091243/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/experience/food-and-wine/2017/02/27/made-connecticut-flavors-only-found-hartford/98263356/ |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> But the New York Times remarked on the diversity of food available in Hartford in 1979, noting that \"Hartford has undergone a culinary revolution in recent years.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brooks |first1=Patricia |title=What's Doing in HARTFORD |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/01/21/archives/whats-doing-in-hartford.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627065907/https://www.nytimes.com/1979/01/21/archives/whats-doing-in-hartford.html |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHartford earned praise from Food and Wine as \"a foodie destination\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Landsel |first1=David |title=A Good Thing Has Happened in Hartford |url=https://www.foodandwine.com/travel/hartford-story-soil-coffee-shop |website=foodandwine.com |publisher=Food and Wine |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627041014/https://www.foodandwine.com/travel/hartford-story-soil-coffee-shop |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Landsel |first1=David |title=Will Food Make People Fall in Love With Hartford? |url=https://www.foodandwine.com/travel/will-food-make-people-fall-in-love-hartford |website=foodandwine.com |publisher=Food and Wine |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626083317/https://www.foodandwine.com/travel/will-food-make-people-fall-in-love-hartford |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Food trucks are restricted to designated areas in the city, mostly along [[Bushnell Park]] in Downtown Hartford and at farmers' markets.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stearns |first1=John |title=Food truck craze spreads across Greater Hartford |url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20170619/PRINTEDITION/306159953/food-truck-craze-spreads-across-greater-hartford |website=hartfordbusiness.com |publisher=Hartford business magazine |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034711/http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20170619/PRINTEDITION/306159953/food-truck-craze-spreads-across-greater-hartford |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Food can today be found throughout the city from a very wide variety of ethnic influence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Connecticut Magazine editorial staff |title=Best Restaurants 2018: Experts' Picks |url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/bests-tops/best-restaurants-experts-picks/article_b0280f0a-e125-11e7-9c46-33f9f1776a85.html |work=Connecticut Magazine |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109113941/http://www.connecticutmag.com/bests-tops/best-restaurants-experts-picks/article_b0280f0a-e125-11e7-9c46-33f9f1776a85.html |archive-date=January 9, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHartford hosts a number of seasonal farmers' markets.<ref>{{cite web |title=West End Farmers Market Strawberry Shortcake Day |url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/calendar/west-end-farmers-market-strawberry-shortcake-day/event_a0103608-6f53-11e8-8a7a-308d99b2d38c.html |work=Connecticut Magazine |accessdate=June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Serving the Community, Satisfying the Palate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/24/nyregion/24dinect.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627074543/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/24/nyregion/24dinect.html |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Hartford Regional Market is the largest market between New York City and Boston.<ref>{{cite web |title=Facts About the Hartford Regional Market |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1370&q=259160 |website=ct.gov |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626082936/http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1370&q=259160 |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, the Connecticut State Assembly voted to transfer ownership of the Regional Market to the Capital Region Development Authority, leaving its future somewhat uncertain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sudden Change in Ownership for Hartford Regional Market |url=http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-hartford-regional-market-redevelopment20180605-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627035240/http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-hartford-regional-market-redevelopment20180605-story.html |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe seashore is less than 35 miles away and has played a large role in Hartford's food habits.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McFarland |first1=Raymond |title=A History of the New England Fisheries: With Maps. |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofnewengl00mcfarich |date=1911 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania |location=New York}}</ref> recently there has been an aquaculture boom in Long Island Sound<ref>{{cite web |last1=Walker Bohm |first1=Jessica |title=Aquaculture Makes Waves in Connecticut |url=https://www.farmflavor.com/connecticut/making-waves-connecticut/ |website=farmflavor.com |publisher=Farm Flavor |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626110917/https://www.farmflavor.com/connecticut/making-waves-connecticut/ |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and as a result local kelp has started to appear on plates.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Luke Groskin and |first1=Brandon Echter |title=Kelp: It's What's For Dinner |url=https://www.sciencefriday.com/videos/kelp-its-whats-for-dinner/ |website=sciencefriday.com |publisher=Science Friday |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627035709/https://www.sciencefriday.com/videos/kelp-its-whats-for-dinner/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Connecticut River Valley is the most agriculturally productive region in New England<ref>''The Traveler's Guide to Western New England and the Connecticut River Valley'' {{ISBN|978-0-679-74413-9}} p. xvi</ref> and neighboring Wethersfield is renowned for its red onions, whose smell was said to waft into Hartford when production was at its historical height in the early 1800s.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Rise and Fall of the Wethersfield Red Onion |url=http://www.newenglandhistoricalsociety.com/rise-fall-wethersfield-red-onion/ |website=newenglandhistory.com |publisher=New England Historical Society |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627062325/http://www.newenglandhistoricalsociety.com/rise-fall-wethersfield-red-onion/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHartford and the surrounding area have a vibrant craft beer, cider, and spirit industry,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Morgan |title=Distinctly Connecticut beer destinations |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/experience/food-and-wine/2018/03/20/connecticut-craft-beer-breweries/437741002/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627041107/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/experience/food-and-wine/2018/03/20/connecticut-craft-beer-breweries/437741002/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kramer |first1=Jack |title=Craft Brewers Call On Lawmakers To Lift Limits |url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/20180306_craft_brewers_call_on_lawmakers_to_lift_limits/ |website=ctnewsjunkie.com |publisher=CT New Junkie |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034310/https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/20180306_craft_brewers_call_on_lawmakers_to_lift_limits/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and there were more than two dozen breweries and distilleries in the Hartford area in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=States Brewers Concerned by SABMiller, Anheuser-Busch InBev Merger |url=http://www.courant.com/community/hartford/hc-hartford-breweries-concerned-20170814-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034645/http://www.courant.com/community/hartford/hc-hartford-breweries-concerned-20170814-story.html |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Connecticut Spirits Trail has a number of stops in Hartford and surrounding towns.<ref>{{cite web |title=CT Spirits Trail Map |url=http://ctspiritstrail.com/map/ |website=ctspiritstrail.com |publisher=Connecticut Spirits Trail |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627090817/http://ctspiritstrail.com/map/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lozier |first1=Chris |title=Building the CT Spirits Trail |url=http://artisanspiritmag.com/building-the-ct-spirits-trail/ |website=artisanspiritmag.com |publisher=Artisan Spirit Magazine |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034703/http://artisanspiritmag.com/building-the-ct-spirits-trail/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> These businesses all feed the city's collection of bars and nightclubs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yuravich |first1=Albie |title=Raise a Glass to Connecticut's Best Bars |url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/food-drink/raise-a-glass-to-connecticut-s-best-bars/article_a4cc53b4-1596-11e8-ab1f-fb71b78d8756.html |work=Connecticut Magazine |accessdate=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311201015/http://www.connecticutmag.com/food-drink/raise-a-glass-to-connecticut-s-best-bars/article_a4cc53b4-1596-11e8-ab1f-fb71b78d8756.html |archive-date=March 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Points of interest===\n[[File:Aetna building in Hartford, Connecticut 2, 2009-09-02.jpg|thumb|Aetna building in the Asylum Hill neighborhood]]\n[[File:Armsmear (Hartford, CT).jpg|thumb|[[Armsmear]]]]\n[[File:Cathedral of Saint Joseph in Hartford 3, 2009-09-02.jpg|thumb|upright|Cathedral of Saint Joseph]]\n[[File:Cheney Building, Hartford CT - main facade composite.jpg|thumb|right|Cheney Building]]\n[[File:Katharine Seymour Day House.jpg|thumb|upright|The house of Katherine Seymour Day, grandniece of Harriet Beecher Stowe adjacent to the [[Harriet Beecher Stowe House (Connecticut)|Stowe]] house; it now forms part of the research center dedicated to Stowe]]\n[[File:Connecticut Science Center.jpg|thumb|upright|Connecticut Science Center on the Riverfront]]\n[[File:Wadsworth Atheneum, Hartford, Connecticut.JPG|thumb|Wadsworth Atheneum]]\n\n*[[Aetna]] building \u2013 Aetna building on Farmington Avenue is the world's largest [[colonial revival]] building, crowned by a tall Georgian tower inspired by the Old State House downtown.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/onehundredyears00jordgoog|title=One Hundred Years of Fire Insurance: Being a History of the \u00c6tna Insurance Company, Hartford, Connecticut, 1819\u20131919|last=Gall|first=Henry Ross|last2=Jordan|first2=William George|date=1919|publisher=\u00c6tna insurance Company|language=en|access-date=May 20, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[First Church of Christ and the Ancient Burying Ground|Ancient Burying Ground]] \u2013 The oldest historic site in Hartford and the city's first graveyard. Many of Hartford's renowned residents and founders are buried there.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://theancientburyingground.org/history/251-2/|title=Center Church {{!}} Hartford's Ancient Burying Ground|website=theancientburyingground.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105031216/http://theancientburyingground.org/history/251-2/|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Armsmear]] \u2013 The Colt family estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=611&ResourceType=Building |title=National Historic Landmarks Program (NHL) |date=October 6, 2007 |access-date=May 20, 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006111906/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=611&ResourceType=Building |archivedate=October 6, 2007 }}</ref>\n*[[Bulkeley Bridge]] \u2013 A stone-arch bridge spanning the Connecticut River and connecting the city of Hartford with East Hartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onenewengland.com/article.php?id=32|title=ONE New England \u2013 The Bulkeley Bridge: An Architectural Treasure|website=onenewengland.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194139/http://www.onenewengland.com/article.php?id=32|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Bushnell Center for the Performing Arts]] \u2013 The theater was constructed in the 1930s by the same architects who designed New York City's [[Radio City Music Hall]]. It features a Georgian Revival exterior and an Art Deco interior, with a large hand-painted mural suspended from the ceiling that is the largest of its kind in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bushnell.org/content/history-archives-landmark-building|title=History, Archives, Landmark Building|work=The Bushnell Performing Arts Center|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419162709/https://bushnell.org/content/history-archives-landmark-building|archive-date=April 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Bushnell Park]] \u2013 This park is located below the State Capitol and legislative office complex and consists of lawn, sculpture, fountains, and a historic carousel. It is the first park in the country purchased by a municipality for public use, and it was designed by [[Jacob Weidenmann]]. The Soldiers & Sailors Civil War Memorial Arch frames the northern entrance to the park, the first [[triumphal arch]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushnellpark.org/about-2/history-2|title=Park History \u2013 Bushnell Park Foundation|website=bushnellpark.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114021010/http://www.bushnellpark.org/about-2/history-2|archive-date=November 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Cathedral of St. Joseph in Hartford|Cathedral of St. Joseph]] \u2013 This {{convert|281|ft|m|adj=on}} limestone Roman Catholic cathedral was built in 1961 to replace its predecessor lost to fire. It is located west of downtown along Farmington Avenue in the Asylum Hill neighborhood and has large Parisian stained glass windows, an 8,000 pipe organ, and the largest ceramic tile mural of Christ in Glory in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cathedralofsaintjoseph.com/|title=Cathedral of Saint Joseph Hartford, Connecticut|website=cathedralofsaintjoseph.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517200126/http://cathedralofsaintjoseph.com/|archive-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[First Church of Christ and the Ancient Burying Ground|Center Church]] \u2013 The First Church of Christ in Hartford is located at 60 Gold Street and is also known as Center Church. It was founded by [[Thomas Hooker]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[Cheney Building]] \u2013 This building was designed in the late 19th-century by [[H. H. Richardson]]. It is located downtown on Main Street and once housed the Brown, Thomson & Co. department store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartfordinfo.org/issues/documents/ArtsandCulture/htfd_courant_092505.asp |title=Massive masterpiece - HartfordInfo.org |date=September 28, 2007 |access-date=May 20, 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928082911/http://www.hartfordinfo.org/issues/documents/ArtsandCulture/htfd_courant_092505.asp |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n*[[Church of the Good Shepherd and Parish House]] - Commissioned by [[Elizabeth Jarvis Colt]] in 1866 and 1895 respectively to commemorate her husband, [[Samuel Colt]], and her son, [[Caldwell Hart Colt]], and designed by [[Edward Tuckerman Potter]]. Both buildings are part of the [[Coltsville Historic District]].\n*[[City Place I]] \u2013 The tallest building in Connecticut at 38 stories, located at 185 Asylum Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/city-place-i/3170|title=City Place I \u2013 The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912022219/http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/city-place-i/3170/|archive-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Colt Armory \u2013 The complex was once the main factory building of [[Colt's Manufacturing Company]], topped with a blue and gold dome. It is currently being redeveloped and renovated and will feature apartments, retail space, and office space.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cttrust.org/index.cgi/7518|title=Connecticut Trust For Historic Preservation|website=cttrust.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703023128/http://cttrust.org/index.cgi/7518|archive-date=July 3, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[The Comcast Theatre|Xfinity Theater]] (formerly the Meadows Music Theater) \u2013 An indoor/outdoor amphitheater-style performance venue located in the North Meadows.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/1997-02-20/entertainment/9702200087_1_sfx-broadcasting-metropolitan-entertainment-bush-show|title=Shift at Meadows Means More Competition in Area Concert Scene|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918022908/http://articles.courant.com/1997-02-20/entertainment/9702200087_1_sfx-broadcasting-metropolitan-entertainment-bush-show|archive-date=September 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Connecticut Science Center]] \u2013 154,000 square foot (14,000&nbsp;m\u00b2), nine-story, $165&nbsp;million museum, designed by [[C\u00e9sar Pelli]] and opened on June 12, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/science/2009-06-12-science-center_N.htm|title=Even before opening, cutbacks at science museum |website=USA Today|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201104507/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/science/2009-06-12-science-center_N.htm|archive-date=February 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Connecticut State Library]] \u2013 The building also contains the Museum of Connecticut History and a number of galleries devoted to [[Samuel Colt]] memorabilia, located in the hill district near the State Capitol atop Bushnell Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ctstatelibrary.org/|title=Connecticut State Library {{!}} Preserving the past. Informing the Future.|website=ctstatelibrary.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525021149/https://ctstatelibrary.org/|archive-date=May 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Connecticut Convention Center]] \u2013 The 540,000 square foot (42,000&nbsp;m\u00b2) convention center is now open and overlooks the Connecticut River and the central business district. Attached to the center is a 409-room, 22-story Marriott Hotel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctconventions.com/|title=Home {{!}} Connecticut Convention Center|website=Connecticut Convention Center|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526225707/http://www.ctconventions.com/|archive-date=May 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[ConnectiCon]] is hosted every summer at the convention center.\n*[[Connecticut Governor's Mansion]] \u2013 An imposing Georgian revival mansion situated near the highest point in the City of Hartford on upper Prospect Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/governorrell/cwp/view.asp?a=1724&Q=276310&PM=1|title=Governor Rell: The Governor's Residence Virtual Tour|last=Governor|first=Office of the|website=ct.gov|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327091013/http://www.ct.gov/governorrell/cwp/view.asp?a=1724&Q=276310&PM=1|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Connecticut Opera]] \u2013 Founded in 1942 and performing three fully staged operas per season, primarily at The Bushnell Center for the Performing Arts in Hartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctopera.org/|title=Home Improvement Guide {{!}} Counter Top Era|website=www.ctopera.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628162639/http://www.ctopera.org/|archive-date=June 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Connecticut State Capitol]] \u2013 This large [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]]-inspired building is located atop Bushnell Park and features many statues and engravings on its exterior. It is topped with a gold-leafed dome.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctheritage.org/encyclopedia/ct1865_1929/newstatecapitol.htm |title=Ctheritage.org |website=ctheritage.org |access-date=May 20, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060306131620/http://www.ctheritage.org/encyclopedia/ct1865_1929/newstatecapitol.htm |archivedate=March 6, 2006 }}</ref>\n*[[Constitution Plaza]] \u2013 Constitution Plaza is a renowned and notorious redevelopment project built in the early 1960s.Hartford's historic Front Street neighborhood was razed to build the plaza. The complex is composed of numerous office buildings, underground parking, a restaurant, a broadcasting studio, and outdoor courtyards and fountains. The area is filled with Christmas lights for the Festival of Light in December. The Plaza passes over I-91 and connects the city to the Connecticut Ri w/|title=Constitution Plaza Then and Now {{!}} ConnecticutHistory.org|website=connecticuthistory.org|access-date=May 20, 2017}}<nowiki></ref></nowiki>\n*[[Dunkin' Donuts Park]] \u2013 A baseball field that opened up on April 13, 2017 to host the Hartford Yard Goats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/sports/baseball/yard-goats/hc-yard-goats-opening-day-20170412-story.html|title=Play Ball! Hartford Yard Goats Take The Field For First Game at Dunkin' Donuts Park|last=GOODE|first=STEVEN|work=courant.com|access-date=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520171232/http://www.courant.com/sports/baseball/yard-goats/hc-yard-goats-opening-day-20170412-story.html|archive-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth Park, Hartford|Elizabeth Park & Rose Garden]] \u2013 A park straddling the border between Hartford and West Hartford.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epcentury.com/ |title=Elizabeth Park A Century of Beauty |publisher=Epcentury.com |accessdate=June 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206062125/http://www.epcentury.com/ |archive-date=February 6, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Harriet Beecher Stowe House (Connecticut)|Harriet Beecher Stowe House]] & Research Center \u2013 The former home of [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] located on [[Nook Farm Connecticut|Nook Farm]] in the Asylum Hill neighborhood on Farmington Avenue. It has become a museum along with its neighbor, the home of Mark Twain.<ref name=\"nk\" />\n*[[The Hartford]] Financial Services Group headquarters campus on Asylum Hill occupies the former site of the [[American School for the Deaf]], which has moved to a campus in West Hartford.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2004/2/prweb107456.htm|title=Two Pioneering Ct. Deaf Organizations Join Forces|work=PRWeb|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316164141/http://www.prweb.com/releases/2004/2/prweb107456.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Hartford Public Library]] \u2013 The Library was founded in 1774 and has over 500,000 holdings, an extensive calendar of programs, and free public access computers and wifi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hplct.org/|title=Hartford Public Library|website=hplct.org|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526224939/https://www.hplct.org/|archive-date=May 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Hartford Symphony Orchestra]] \u2013 Connecticut's regional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hartfordsymphony.org/|title=Hartford Symphony Orchestra {{!}} Connecticut's Premier Musical Organization|website=hartfordsymphony.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523174741/https://hartfordsymphony.org/|archive-date=May 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The [[Hartt School]] at the University of Hartford is recognized as one of the premiere performing arts conservatories in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartford.edu/hartt/|title=The Hartt School|website=hartford.edu|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524132219/http://www.hartford.edu/hartt/|archive-date=May 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The [[Mark Twain House]] and Museum \u2013 The home was built by [[Mark Twain|Samuel Clemens]] and his wife in 1874. They lived here 17 years, raising three daughters. This is where Mark Twain wrote many of his most popular books. The house is open year-round for tours, events, and author programs. It is located in Nook Farm,<ref name=\"nk\">{{cite web|title=Stowe's Hartford Neighborhood, Nook Farm|url=https://www.harrietbeecherstowecenter.org/hbs/nook_farm.shtml|publisher=Harriet Beecher Stowe Center|access-date=May 5, 2016|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170704040524/https://www.harrietbeecherstowecenter.org/hbs/nook_farm.shtml|archive-date=July 4, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> part of the Asylum Hill neighborhood on Farmington Avenue. ''National Geographic'' named it one of the ten best historic homes in the world.<ref>Lande, Nathaniel; Lande, Andrew. ''The 10 Best of Everything, Third Edition: An Ultimate Guide for Travelers (National Geographic the 10 Best of Everything)'' (New York: National Geographic, 2012), p. 60\u20131.</ref>\n*[[Old State House (Hartford)|Old State House]] \u2013 The Old State House dates back to 1796, making it one of the nation's oldest. It was designed by [[Charles Bulfinch]], who also designed the [[Massachusetts State House]] in Boston. It was recently restored with a gold-leafed dome and sits facing the Connecticut River in downtown. It was the site of the [[United States v. The Amistad]] trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cga.ct.gov/osh/|title=Connecticut's Old State House|website=cga.ct.gov|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422193912/https://www.cga.ct.gov/osh/|archive-date=April 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Phoenix Life Insurance Company Building]] \u2013 The first two-sided building in the world, located on [[Constitution Plaza]] and listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://connecticuthistory.org/the-phoenix-building-hartford/|title=The Phoenix Building, Hartford {{!}} ConnecticutHistory.org|website=connecticuthistory.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601043150/http://connecticuthistory.org/the-phoenix-building-hartford/|archive-date=June 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Polish National Home (Hartford, Connecticut)|Polish National Home]] \u2013 Opened in 1930 to serve the Polish community that once dominated this part of Hartford, the building now serves as restaurant and banquet hall.<ref>{{cite web |title=Polish National Home |url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP/GetAsset/NRHP/83003566_text |publisher=United States Department of the Interior |date=September 12, 1983 |access-date=June 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622225936/https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP/GetAsset/NRHP/83003566_text |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hartford PNH |url=http://polishhomect.org/ |accessdate=June 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622032005/http://polishhomect.org/ |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Pope Park, Hartford, Connecticut|Pope Park]] \u2013 Public park originally landscaped by the [[Olmsted Brothers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crja.com/project/pope-park-master-plan/|title=Pope Park Master Plan {{!}} CRJA|website=CRJA|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618210954/http://crja.com/project/pope-park-master-plan/|archive-date=June 18, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Real Art Ways]] \u2013 An alternative art gallery hosting contemporary art, music, and film productions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-10-21/entertainment/hc-raw-35-1021-20101021_1_35th-anniversary-mel-chin-roxy-paine|title=Real Art Ways Marks 35 Years and Counting|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621202216/http://articles.courant.com/2010-10-21/entertainment/hc-raw-35-1021-20101021_1_35th-anniversary-mel-chin-roxy-paine|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Arch]] \u2013 This brownstone memorial is located in Bushnell Park to honor the 4,000 Hartford citizens who served in the [[American Civil War]], and the 400 who perished. It was the first [[triumphal arch]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=11954OX725657.419&profile=ariall&uri=link=3100009~!1163650~!3100001~!3100002&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=1&source=~!siartinventories&term=Soldiers+and+Sailors+Memorial+Arch,&index=ALTIT|title=Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Arch|last=Keller|first=George W.|last2=Entress|first2=Albert|last3=Buberl|first3=Caspar|last4=Kitson|first4=Samuel James|last5=Bissell|first5=Hiram|last6=Budde|first6=Augustus|date=1884|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622005311/https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=11954OX725657.419&profile=ariall&uri=link=3100009~!1163650~!3100001~!3100002&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=1&source=~!siartinventories&term=Soldiers+and+Sailors+Memorial+Arch,&index=ALTIT|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Trinity College, Hartford|Trinity College]] \u2013 The liberal arts college was founded in 1823 and has more than 2,100 students. It is the second-oldest in Connecticut after [[Yale University]] in [[New Haven]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Unitarian Meeting House, Hartford|Unitarian Meeting House]] (1964) - a modernist structure designed by [[Victor A. Lundy]].<ref>[https://www.ushartford.com/about-us/about-our-building/ Unitarian Society of Hartford - About our building]</ref>\n*[[University of Connecticut]] Hartford Campus \u2013 The downtown campus of the University of Connecticut, anchored on Prospect Street by the historic [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] entrance of the former Hartford Times building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hartford.uconn.edu/|title=UConn Hartford homepage|website=hartford.uconn.edu|access-date=September 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045043/http://hartford.uconn.edu/|archive-date=September 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[University of Connecticut School of Business]] \u2013 A branch of the University of Connecticut Business school operates in downtown Hartford on Market Street, north of Constitution Plaza.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business.uconn.edu/about/campuses/hartford/|title=Hartford Campus {{!}} School of Business|website=www.business.uconn.edu|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523081613/http://www.business.uconn.edu/about/campuses/hartford|archive-date=May 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[University of Connecticut School of Law]] \u2013 The campus is located off Farmington Avenue and features an extensive Gothic-inspired library.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.uconn.edu/|title=Welcome to UConn School of Law {{!}} UConn School of Law|website=www.law.uconn.edu|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522075418/https://www.law.uconn.edu/|archive-date=May 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[University of Hartford]] \u2013 The university was founded in 1877 and sits on {{convert|340|acre}} with a {{convert|13|acre|adj=on}} campus on Bloomfield Avenue situated on land divided among Hartford, West Hartford, and Bloomfield in the Blue Hills neighborhood.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*[[Wadsworth Atheneum]] Museum of Art \u2013 The oldest art museum in the US is located on Main Street in downtown Hartford opposite the Travelers Tower.  The museum features a significant collection of Italian Baroque old masters and post-impressionist modern art. [[Alexander Calder]]'s Stegosaurus sculpture sits in a plaza between it and the Hartford Municipal Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/pdfhost/docs/NRHP/Text/70000709.pdf|title=NATIONAL REGISTER OF HISTORIC PLACES INVENTORY \u2013 NOMINATION FORM|date=October 6, 1970|website=nps.gov|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]]|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223092133/https://npgallery.nps.gov/pdfhost/docs/NRHP/Text/70000709.pdf|archive-date=February 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[XL Center]] \u2013 The center hosts concerts and shows and is home to the [[Hartford Wolf Pack]] AHL hockey team and the [[Connecticut Huskies]] basketball team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xlcenter.com/|title=XL CENTER|last=CENTER|first=XL|website=xlcenter.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526230400/http://www.xlcenter.com/|archive-date=May 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Parades===\n\n* Greater Hartford St. Patrick's Day Parade \u2013 [[Downtown Hartford|Downtown]] \u2013 March \u2013 Run by The Central Connecticut Celtic Cultural Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishamericanparade.com/|title=Hartford St. Patrick's Day Parade|website=irishamericanparade.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529054225/http://www.irishamericanparade.com/|archive-date=May 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Greater Hartford Puerto Rican Day Parade \u2013 [[Downtown Hartford|Downtown]], [[South Green, Hartford|South Green]], and [[Neighborhoods of Hartford, Connecticut#Frog Hollow|Frog Hollow]] \u2013 June \u2013 Run by The Connecticut Institute for Community Development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hartfordprparade.com/|title=2017 CICD Hartford PR Parade|website=hartfordprparade.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110194728/https://hartfordprparade.com/|archive-date=November 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Greater Hartford West Indian Parade \u2013 [[Northeast, Hartford|Northeast]] \u2013 August \u2013 Run by The West Indian Independence Celebrations since 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiichartford.org/events.html|title=Events|website=wiichartford.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814024645/http://www.wiichartford.org/events.html|archive-date=August 14, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Hooker Day Parade \u2013 [[Downtown Hartford|Downtown]] \u2013 May \u2013 Run by Hartford Business Improvement District.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/entertainment/music/hc-hooker-day-parade-offers-eclectic-music-lineup-20170406-story.html|title=Revamped Hooker Day Parade & Fest Announces Musical Lineup|last=HAMAD|first=MICHAEL|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422010343/http://www.courant.com/entertainment/music/hc-hooker-day-parade-offers-eclectic-music-lineup-20170406-story.html|archive-date=April 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Connecticut Veterans Parade \u2013 [[Downtown Hartford|Downtown]] \u2013 November \u2013 Run by The Ferris Group, LLC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ctveteransparade.org/|title=Connecticut Veterans Parade|date=November 6, 2016|website=|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709205454/https://ctveteransparade.org/|archive-date=July 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Recent developments==\n[[File:NovaBUS LFX.jpg|thumb|[[CTfastrak]] was built to connect the suburbs to Hartford.]]\n* Adriaen's Landing \u2013 The state and privately funded project is situated on the banks of the Connecticut River along Columbus Boulevard, and connects to Constitution Plaza. Constitution Plaza forced hundreds of households to relocate when it was built a few decades ago. The latest project includes the {{convert|540000|sqft|m2|-3|adj=on}} Connecticut Convention Center, which opened in June 2005 and is the largest meeting space between New York City and [[Boston]].  Attached to the Convention Center is the 22-story, 409-room [[Marriott International|Marriott]] Hartford Hotel-Downtown, which opened in August 2005. Being constructed next to the convention center and hotel is the {{convert|140000|sqft|m2|-3|adj=on}} Connecticut Science Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crdact.net/regional_development/adriaens_landing.html|title=Adriaen's Landing|website=crdact.net|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629033251/http://crdact.net/regional_development/adriaens_landing.html|archive-date=June 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Capital Community College]] at the 11-story G. Fox Department Store Building \u2013 The {{convert|913000|sqft|m2|-2|adj=on}} former home of the [[G. Fox & Co.|G. Fox & Company Department Store]] on Main Street has been renovated and made the new home of Capital Community College as well as offices for the State of Connecticut and ground level retail space. Capital Community College helps train (mostly) adult students in specific career fields. On Thursdays, vendors sell crafts on the Main Street level. Two music clubs, Mezzanine and Room 960, are housed in the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.capitalcc.edu/|title=Capital Community College {{!}}|website=www.capitalcc.edu|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509084157/https://www.capitalcc.edu/|archive-date=May 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[CTfastrak]] \u2013 The recently completed [[bus rapid transit]] system connects Hartford's Union Station to downtown New Britain. It was built to ease traffic on [[Interstate 84 in Connecticut|I-84]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ctfastrak.com/about/news/news-releases/13-media-releases/279-03-28-15-despite-snow-thousands-of-riders-many-first-timers-experience-ctfastrak-on-first-day-of-service|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911222239/http://ctfastrak.com/about/news/news-releases/13-media-releases/279-03-28-15-despite-snow-thousands-of-riders-many-first-timers-experience-ctfastrak-on-first-day-of-service|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 11, 2015|title=CTfastrak.com \u2013 (03/28/15) Despite Snow, Thousands of Riders, Many First-Timers, Experience CTfastrak on First Day of Service|date=September 11, 2015|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref>\n*Front Street \u2013 The final component of Adriaen's Landing, Front Street, sits across from the Convention Center and covers the land between Columbus Boulevard and [[The Hartford Times Building]]. The Front Street development combines retail, entertainment and residential components. Publicly funded parts of the project will include transportation improvements. There have been significant delays in the Front Street project, and the first developer was removed from the project because of lack of progress. The city has chosen a new developer, but work is yet to begin on the retail and residential component of Front Street. The city and state may soon take action to increase the speed with which the project enters implementation phases. There has been talk of bringing an [[ESPN Zone]] to the Front Street ([[ESPN]] is headquartered in nearby [[Bristol, Connecticut|Bristol]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontstreetdistrict.com/index.html |title=The New Pulse of Hartford &#124; Home |publisher=Front Street District |accessdate=June 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326123201/http://www.frontstreetdistrict.com/index.html |archivedate=March 26, 2012 }}</ref> On the back side of Front Street, the historic [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] Hartford Times Building is being converted into a downtown campus of the [[University of Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gosselin|first1=Kenneth|title=Authority Gets Look at Latest UConn Hartford Campus Renderings|url=http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-uconn-hartford-connecticut-campus-new-renderings-20141121-story.html|newspaper=The Hartford Courant|date=November 21, 2014|access-date=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402012736/http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-uconn-hartford-connecticut-campus-new-renderings-20141121-story.html|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Hartford Line]] \u2013 According to Connecticut Governor Malloy, the Hartford Line commuter rail service will reach speeds up to {{convert|110|mph|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"nhregister.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nhregister.com/articles/2011/04/07/news/doc4d9cf8b24e8c3339028689.txt |title=Conn. seeks funds for rail work on Hartford-to-Springfield line (document) |newspaper=The New Haven Register |date=April 7, 2011 |accessdate=June 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419101014/http://www.nhregister.com/articles/2011/04/07/news/doc4d9cf8b24e8c3339028689.txt |archive-date=April 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The rail line is intended to unite the densely populated, {{convert|61|mi|disp=or|abbr=on}}) region between Hartford, Springfield, and New Haven; ease the frequently congested [[Interstate 91]] automobile highway; and increase mobility in a region that is now almost entirely dependent upon automobile ownership. As of May 2011, Connecticut's portion of the commuter line has been 3/4 funded. Currently, the state is seeking the $227&nbsp;million necessary to complete the northern portion of the line from the $2.4&nbsp;billion in Federal funds that Florida rejected to fund its own high-speed rail project.<ref name=\"nhregister.com\" />\n*Knowledge Corridor Partnership \u2013 In 2000, at [[The Big E]] in [[West Springfield, Massachusetts]], Hartford and Springfield, Massachusetts \u2013 the two major New England, [[Connecticut River Valley]] cities with centers only {{convert|24|mi|disp=or|abbr=on}}) apart \u2013 jointly announced the [[Knowledge Corridor]] Partnership. The Knowledge Corridor Partnership aims to unite the two metropolitan areas economically, culturally, and geographically. The nickname comes from the metropolitan region's over 32 universities and liberal arts colleges, including several of the United States' most prestigious. As of the 10th anniversary of the Knowledge Corridor, it was announced that the Knowledge Corridor is beginning to receive federal funds, as opposed to either state or city.<ref>{{cite web |author=The Republican file photo |url=http://www.masslive.com/business-news/index.ssf/2010/10/hartford_springfield_economic_partnershi.html |title=Hartford Springfield Economic Partnership gets $4.2&nbsp;million to boost Knowledge Corridor |publisher=masslive.com |accessdate=June 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925033206/http://www.masslive.com/business-news/index.ssf/2010/10/hartford_springfield_economic_partnershi.html |archive-date=September 25, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*New condos and apartments:\n** Spectra Boutique Apartments \u2013 The former 300 room Sonesta Hotel at 5 Constitution Plaza was converted into 190 luxury rental apartments in 2015 by New York City Developers Girona Ventures and Wonder Works Construction & Development Corp. The building was awarded the Best of Hartford: 2017 for Best Upscale Apartment Building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/hartford-magazine/best-of/home/hc-hm-best-upscale-apartment-complex-20170324-story.html|title=Best Upscale Apartment Complex|last=Courant|first=Hartford|work=courant.com|access-date=July 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712002211/http://www.courant.com/hartford-magazine/best-of/home/hc-hm-best-upscale-apartment-complex-20170324-story.html|archive-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n** Hartford 21 \u2013 On the site of the former Hartford Civic Center Mall (now known as the XL Center), the project includes a 36-story residential tower\u2014the tallest residential tower between New York City and Boston, and is located at the intersection of Trumbull Street and Asylum Street. Attached to the tower is 90,000 square feet (8,000&nbsp;m\u00b2) of office space and 45,000 square feet (4,200&nbsp;m\u00b2) of retail space, all contained within a connected complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartford21.com/|title=Hartford 21 Apartment Living \u2013 Look no further for your Hartford apartment rental.|website=Hartford 21|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524215031/http://www.hartford21.com/|archive-date=May 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n** Trumbull on the Park \u2013 Recently opened along Bushnell Park, this apartment community is housed in a new 11-story brick building along with a parking garage and ground-level retail space. Additional units are housed in recently renovated historic buildings on nearby Lewis Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trumbullapts.com/|title=Luxury Hartford CT Apartments {{!}} Trumbull on the Park|website=www.trumbullapts.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516095639/http://www.trumbullapts.com/|archive-date=May 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n** Sage Allen Building \u2013 On Main Street, the former Sage Allen department store building has been turned into 44 4-bedroom townhouses as well as an upscale apartment building comprising about 70 units that opened in January 2007. The project also includes the renovation of the Richardson Food Court and the reopening of Temple Street, which once again reconnects Main and Market Streets. Many of the townhouses will be occupied by [[University of Hartford]] students. It sits directly across Market Street from the [[University of Connecticut]] Graduate Business Learning Center.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/1998-12-11/news/9812110328_1_housing-project-office-building-sage-allen|title=Sage-allen Building May Be History|work=tribunedigital-thecourant|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622170508/http://articles.courant.com/1998-12-11/news/9812110328_1_housing-project-office-building-sage-allen|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n** American Airlines Building \u2013 Located at 915 Main Street across from Capital Community College and the [[Residence Inn by Marriott]], the site was formerly home to an [[E. J. Korvette]] department store and later American Airlines. The building has been converted into apartments with renovated ground-level retail space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20080218/PRINTEDITION/302189991/new-apartments-available-in-downtown-hartford--developer-of-american-airlines-building-looking-for-tenants|title=New Apartments Available in Downtown Hartford {{!}} Developer of American Airlines building looking for tenants|work=Hartford Business Journal|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622164937/http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20080218/PRINTEDITION/302189991/new-apartments-available-in-downtown-hartford--developer-of-american-airlines-building-looking-for-tenants|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main list|List of people from Hartford, Connecticut}}\n\nHartford has been home to many historically significant people, such as dictionary author [[Noah Webster]] (1758\u20131843), inventor [[Sam Colt]] (1814\u201362), and American financier and industrialist [[J.P. Morgan]] (1837\u20131913).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://connecticuthistory.org/noah-webster-and-the-dream-of-a-common-language/|title=Noah Webster and the Dream of a Common Language {{!}} ConnecticutHistory.org|website=connecticuthistory.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819190917/https://connecticuthistory.org/noah-webster-and-the-dream-of-a-common-language/|archive-date=August 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/courant-250/moments-in-history/hc-250-p3-sam-colt-innovation-in-connecticut-20141224-story.html|title=Part 3: An Industrial Ecosystem Emerges Around Sam Colt's Guns|last=HAAR|first=DAN|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105021654/http://www.courant.com/courant-250/moments-in-history/hc-250-p3-sam-colt-innovation-in-connecticut-20141224-story.html|archive-date=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://connecticuthistory.org/j-p-morgans-connecticut-roots/|title=J. P. Morgan's Connecticut Roots {{!}} ConnecticutHistory.org|website=connecticuthistory.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501231436/http://connecticuthistory.org/j-p-morgans-connecticut-roots/|archive-date=May 1, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome of America's most famous authors lived in Hartford, including [[Mark Twain]] (1835\u20131910), who moved to the city in 1874. Twain's next-door neighbor at Nook Farm was [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] (1811\u201396). Poet [[Wallace Stevens]] (1879\u20131955) was an insurance executive in the city, and World War II correspondent [[Lyn Crost]] (1915\u201397) lived there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marktwainhouse.org/man/biography_main.php|title=Welcome to the Mark Twain House & Museum \u2013 Biography of Mark Twain|website=marktwainhouse.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512074002/http://www.marktwainhouse.org/man/biography_main.php|archive-date=May 12, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harrietbeecherstowecenter.org/|title=Welcome to the Harriet Beecher Stowe Center|website=harrietbeecherstowecenter.org|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519152249/http://www.harrietbeecherstowecenter.org/|archive-date=May 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/travel/for-the-poet-wallace-stevens-hartford-was-an-unlikely-muse.html|title=For the Poet Wallace Stevens, Hartford Was an Unlikely Muse|last=Gordinier|first=Jeff|date=February 23, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404142441/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/travel/for-the-poet-wallace-stevens-hartford-was-an-unlikely-muse.html|archive-date=April 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theindy.org/a/996|title=Writing the War: The Story of Lyn Crost B'38|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201065248/http://www.theindy.org/a/996|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> More recently, [[Dominick Dunne]] (1925\u20132009), [[John Gregory Dunne]] (1932\u20132003), and [[Suzanne Collins]] (born 1962) have resided in Hartford.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/courant-250/moments-in-history/hc-whos-who-in-connecticut-arts-and-culture-wr-005-photo.html|title=DOMINICK DUNNE (1925\u20132009)|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2004/03/dunne200403|title=A Death in the Family|last=Dunne|first=Dominick|work=The Hive|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615170205/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2004/03/dunne200403|archive-date=June 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/hc-famous-people-that-call-hartford-home-20130-005-photo.html|title=Suzanne Collins|last=Courant|first=Hartford|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nActors and others in the entertainment business from Hartford include Academy Award-winning film icon [[Katharine Hepburn]], actors [[Thomas Ian Griffith]], [[Gary Merrill]], [[Linda Evans]], [[Eriq La Salle]], [[Diane Venora]], [[William Gillette]], and [[Charles Nelson Reilly]], and TV producer and writer [[Norman Lear]]. [[Marvel Comics]] artist [[George Tuska]] grew up in Hartford.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/search/name?birth_place=Hartford,%20Connecticut,%20USA|title=IMDb: Most Popular People Born In \"Hartford/ Connecticut/ USA\"|website=IMDb|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622025326/http://www.imdb.com/search/name?birth_place=Hartford,%20Connecticut,%20USA|archive-date=June 22, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Barbara McClintock]] (1902\u20131992), pioneering [[cytogenetics|cytogeneticist]] was born in Hartford, CT. She was awarded the 1983 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for the breakthrough discovery of [[Transposable element|genetic transposition]]. She is the only woman to receive an unshared Nobel Prize in the Medicine category.\n\n[[Frederick Law Olmsted]] (1822\u20131903), considered the father of the profession of [[Landscape Architecture]], was born in Hartford. Among his designs are New York's [[Central Park]], [[World's Columbian Exposition|1893 Chicago World's Fair]], and Asheville's [[Biltmore Estate]].  Other projects that Olmsted was involved in include the country's first and oldest coordinated system of public parks and parkways in Buffalo, New York; the country's oldest state park, the Niagara Reservation in Niagara Falls, New York; one of the first planned communities in the United States, Riverside, Illinois; Mount Royal Park in Montreal, Quebec; the Emerald Necklace in Boston, Massachusetts; Highland Park in Rochester, New York; Belle Isle Park, in the Detroit River for Detroit, Michigan; the Grand Necklace of Parks in Milwaukee, Wisconsin; Cherokee Park and entire parks and parkway system in Louisville, Kentucky.\n\nIn the field of music, natives include singer [[Sophie Tucker]] (1884\u20131966), \"last of the red-hot mamas.\" Others include:\n*Rock and Roll Hall of Fame members [[Gene Pitney]] and Mike Carabello (of [[Santana (band)|Santana]])\n*[[Mark McGrath]]\n*bass guitarist [[Doug Wimbish]] of [[Living Colour]]\n*[[Cindy Blackman]] (drummer for [[Lenny Kravitz]])\n*jazz alto saxophonist [[Jackie McLean]]<ref>Dixon, Ken, \"Music Hall of Fame proposed for state\", article in ''Connecticut Post'' in Bridgeport, Connecticut, April 26, 2007 (\"Other famous state residents include the late jazz saxophonist Jackie McLean of Hartford\")</ref>\n*concert violinist [[Elmar Oliveira]] (b. 1950)\n*brothers [[Jeff Porcaro]], [[Mike Porcaro]], and [[Steve Porcaro]] (of the group [[Toto (band)|Toto]])\n\nFormer [[Cleveland Browns]] head coach [[Eric Mangini]] is from Hartford.  Former NHL player [[Craig Janney]] and current player [[Nick Bonino]] were born in Hartford.  Other sports stars include NBA players [[Marcus Camby]], [[Rick Mahorn]], [[Johnny Egan]], and [[Michael Adams (basketball)|Michael Adams]], as well as NFL kicker [[John Carney (American football)|John Carney]], [[Dwight Freeney]], [[Tebucky Jones]], and [[Eugene Robinson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/sports/hc-connecticut-olympian-capsules-20160803-story.html|title=Local Olympians: Athletes, Coaches With Ties To Connecticut|work=courant.com|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116071709/http://www.courant.com/sports/hc-connecticut-olympian-capsules-20160803-story.html|archive-date=November 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Sister cities==\nHartford features numerous [[sister cities]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.db-city.com/United-States--Connecticut--Hartford--Hartford|title=Hartford|publisher=DB City.com|accessdate=February 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220174628/http://en.db-city.com/United-States--Connecticut--Hartford--Hartford|archive-date=February 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> They include:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{flagdeco|ISR}} [[Afula]], Israel\n* {{flagdeco|POL}} [[Bydgoszcz]], Poland\n* {{flagdeco|PRI}} [[Caguas]], Puerto Rico\n* {{flagdeco|TTO}} [[Couva]], Trinidad and Tobago\n* {{flagdeco|PRC}} [[Dongguan]], Guangdong, China\n* {{flagdeco|ITA}} [[Floridia]], Sicily, Italy\n* {{flagdeco|SLE}} [[Freetown]], Sierra Leone\n* {{flagdeco|UK}} [[Hertford]], Hertfordshire, United Kingdom\n* {{flagdeco|BRA}} [[Jo\u00e3o Pessoa, Para\u00edba|Jo\u00e3o Pessoa]], Brazil\n* {{flagdeco|PRT}} [[Mangualde]], Portugal\n* {{flagdeco|JAM}} [[Morant Bay]], Jamaica\n* {{flagdeco|IRE}} [[New Ross]], Ireland\n* {{flagdeco|NIC}} [[Ocotal]], Nicaragua\n* {{flagdeco|GRC}} [[Thessaloniki]], Greece\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n*[[Hartford Electric Light Company]]\n*[[Mary-Ann (turbine generator)]]\n*[[List of cities in Connecticut]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=Hartford|commons=Category:Hartford, Connecticut|b=no|n=no|q=no|s=no|v=no|voy=Hartford|species=no|d=Q33486}}\n*{{official website|http://www.hartford.gov}}\n* [http://www.metrohartford.com/ Chamber of Commerce]\n* {{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** {{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Hartford |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite Americana |last=Morgan |first=Forrest |wstitle=Hartford (Connecticut)|display=Hartford, Conn.|short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Hartford |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite CE1913 |last=Duggan |first=Thomas Stephen |wstitle=Diocese of Hartford |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Hartford |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Hartford|year=1905 |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite EB9|wstitle=Hartford|volume=11 |short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{Cite AmCyc|wstitle=Hartford (city)|display=Hartford, a city in the town of the same name|first=J. W. |last=Hawes |short=x |noicon=x}}\n}}\n\n{{Hartford, Connecticut}} \n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Hartford, Connecticut\n|North     =